column6: In Style Eyes Wall Street II, Stylish Classic Look Spring Hinged Reading Glasses
column13: Good Style Concept in Reading Glasses but Poor Execution and Misleading Photograph. Not durable, broken in one month.
column14:
Negatives

1. Picture does not accurately represent what I received. The sides on the pair I received are a light, clear orange color that does not match the tortoise shell portion of the front frame.

2. Instead of more durable plastic, the main side arms are weak and thin metal with tiny screws of just the type that fall out in a little bit of time.

3. One main reason to pay so much for "reading" glasses is style, however another reason would be a durable design.

4. Spring loaded hinges that should be a "plus" are more of an issue because they have parts to fall out and break.

5. Style looks good from the front, shoddy on the sides.

On the plus side (two stars):

1. Lens quality is quite clear and good.

2. Glasses come with a very nice case.

If you're looking for the more durable all plastic clunky frame type setup that can handle hooking on a tee shirt neck or tossing in a pocket, these are not it. Also, if you want more consistent style, maybe Orvis (but much more money).

If you are gentle on your reading glasses and also, if you don't care what they look like other than looking at yourself in the mirror directly, you may enjoy these glasses. If I find out that the seller has changed the photograph to show what I received, I'll add a star. If they break or have further issues in 90 days or less, I'm knocking a star.

Edit Sept. 6, 2015

The right arm fell off. Now I have one out of two pairs left. The picture has not changed, and one of two pair are broken. Knocking another star.

Edit August 25, 2016
It has been several months since the arm broke off of the second pair that I barely used. Two out of two pairs failed. Not going to update this review anymore.

column13: Perfect shoe for a new runner
column14:
Love this shoe! I started running just this year in traditional 8 mm drop shoes from a major brand, with stiff arch support inserts. After a knee injury, I started reading into running technique and discovered the benefits of zero drop shoes, minimalist shoes. I bought another pair of Altra's with light padding and really like them. I bought this pair because they have "medium padding" and I'm using them just to get started since I run on concrete and want extra padding while I toughen up my tendons.

What I love most about these shoes is the roomy toe box. Why is it so hard to find shoes that shaped like real feet?! I am DONE with cramming my toes into shoes that are not shaped like a real foot.

column6: Saucony Women's Ride 6 Running Shoe
column14: I have high arches and somewhat wide feet and for many years Saucony neutral shoes were my go-to running shoes. When the first versions of Saucony Ride came out I found the soles far too soft so that my landings felt unstable.  But when at last the Ride 6 was made available, I knew I'd found my way back to Saucony.  Though I have always worn a size 6.5 street shoe and a 7 med. running shoe, I had to buy a 7.5 medium in the Ride 6 in the citron color.  Because they were so comfortable ( they do not have a lot of arch support, so I replaced the factory insoles with arch insoles), I ordered another pair in silver-gray/green in a 7.5 medium but, upon running in them, I found they were half size too long and altered my stride. Since it was too late to send them back, I've kept them for dog walking but it seems wrong and is rather frustrating to discover that an athletic shoe company like Saucony would manufacture shoes that vary in size depending on which color one buys.  To my mind, this is the source of customers' various reviews with regard to fit; there is a lack of consistency when it comes to sizing.

column6: Gentle Souls Women's Joy Platform Sandal
column14: I saw these gladiator wedges just recently and just had to have them!  They look just like the "Break My Heart" flat gladiator sandals made popular by Gentle Souls.  I have several pairs of the "Break My Heart" gladiator sandal and really love them, so I figured this wedge would be a great addition to my ever-growing shoe wardrobe.  I take an 8 or 8 1/2 B width, depending upon the manufacturer.  Since the reviews indicated this shoe ran a bit big, I ordered the size 8, and the fit is spot-on. My toes don't spill over the top of the sandal and the sides of my feet are not squeezed by the straps and ties. The color is a nice neutral - like a stone beige - that goes with everything.  I wore these sandals most of the day, in hot weather, standing and walking, and did not experience any foot aches or pains.  However, the reason I rated this 4 stars instead of 5 is because of the way the shoe is designed.  The platform is rigid and doesn't bend with your foot.  As a result, the heel part is not flexible, and is not as snug as it should be. So my heel slips up and down with each step.  Will probably get some heel inserts to minimize this issue.  Other than that complaint, I like these shoes - they are pretty, stylish and fashion-forward.

column6: Women's Western Cowboy Boots - Calf High - Several Colors
column13: I enjoy line dancing and take classes two nights a week ...
column14: I enjoy line dancing and take classes two nights a week and try to get in at least one night of social dancing every month. I have wanted a pair of western cowboy boots for quite some time but the ones I see have been at least $100 and up in price.  I saw these boots and figured I would give them a try.  Well, don‚Äôt assume the cheaper price means cheaper quality.  These boots are nearly perfect! The leather material is soft and comfortable on the leg and foot.  It moves well and is not stiff.  The toe bed is a little narrower than I am used to, which might stretch some as I continue to wear them.  I have a larger than normal ankle due to a fracture and surgery over six years ago, but the scar tissue and mobility remains a problem. I have trouble with taller boots when I have to point and bend the foot to slip it in.  I also have large calves so I was concerned about being able to get the boots on.  They are advertised as fitting a 14-15‚Äù inch calf and there is plenty of room, even with jeans on.  The tabs on the side of the boot also help with getting them on easily.  I ordered a 6.5 which is my normal street shoe size and I would say they run true to size.  If you have a wide foot however you might want to go up in size as the toe does narrow to a point. I ordered these boots in black, as when we line dance our outfits are black jeans or skirts.  There is some detailed stitching on the boots giving them that western flair.  I don‚Äôt think the design is as noticeable on the black as on the brown.  The heel is a great height at around 2 inches, so you remain steady on your feet and don‚Äôt have to worry about a higher heel throwing you off balance when you spin and turn, but you still have a raised heel for heel taps or stomping, making the line dancing all the more fun and enjoyable. I received this product at a discounted price in exchange for my honest and unbiased review.  I would recommend this boot to anyone who enjoys the western look of cowboy boots, they are so cute with jeans or shorts for that casual cowgirl look.  I would buy them again in another color.

column6: Reef Men's Fanning Speed Logo Sandal
column14:
WORST pair of Reefs I've ever purchased.
When possible I wear flip flops to do EVERYTHING! That being said I bought these Reefs after my last pair (which lasted about 14 months) fell apart. I thought the "cushioning" would make them last longer and be more comfortable. Problem is the air bubble is COMPLETELY cosmetic. As with any air cushioning (think Nike Air MAX) there is a structure inside that is supposed to provide some support to the air bubbly. The structure inside this is so hard that at no point does the air bubble flex to provide any sort of cushioning. This in effect places your heal about 3/4" off the ground and the only cushioning provided is about 1/4" of foam.
After wearing these flip flops for a week my feet and knees hurt worst then they ever have. The arch support is almost non existent and because the heal doesn't absorb any impact the sandals create an almost "high heel" type situation. Not sure what the other 3000 people found great about these sandals?!?

I've worn them every day since I got back including jogging on the treadmill and they have been comfortable. The logo on the side is subtle enough that I wore these to nice restaurants and clubs.

column6: Demonia by Pleaser Men's Trashville-518 Goth Boot
column14:
When I received these boots in the mail, I was ecstatic. I'd been waiting somewhere shy of five days to finally open the door and see them on my doorstep. You can imagine my delight at waking up from a nap to see a massive box sitting on the stoop, knowing what was inside.
First let's talk about the packaging. They came in a shoe box, the label on top deeming that they were indeed the boots. Open them up and they were separated by a cardboard lining with individual wrappings for each boot. Nice.
Now comes the meat and potatoes of this venture: putting them on. Firstly it took around fifteen minutes for me to lace and unbuckle the both of them and another twenty to put just one of them on. The fit was, well, a little too large and especially spacious in the toe but they are easy to walk around in so long as you mind where you're putting your feet.
Now, my calves are quite large and I will have to put another hole in the top straps in order for them to buckle, and if you have large calves like myself you might find some difficulty in lacing them up. If you use the standard lacing method you might not even be able to loop them through the top loops.
For this I recommend the double helix lace.
All and all very nice boots. The shine is something I quite enjoy and there were no imperfections.
Here is the part where I offer some advice: if you want these boots to last, zip them up before you lace them and be sure to completely unlace and unbuckle them before you take them off/put them back on. The zipper may seem strong, but put enough pressure on it and no doubt it'll break. Trust me on this I've ruined a pair of boots by thinking I could just zip them on without unlacing them.

column6: DailyShoes Women's Fashion-Hi Over-the-Knee Thigh High Flat Slouchly Shaft Low Heel Boots
column13: 2 1/2 Stars Really, I'm on the Fence, But the Smell!!!! big thumbs down!!!
column14:
I find it interesting that of the many reviews, (though I didn't read all of them) I didn't come across ANY that mentioned the SMELL. As soon as I opened the mailing envelope, a very strong moth ball mixed with chemicals smell hit me! I'm not sure if it's because they were out on my porch in the heat for a few hours since delivery, but it always makes me leery when I smell that because I wonder where the product was manufactured & WITH WHAT exactly!! They are very nice and soft, DEFINITELY need an insert for support because you are otherwise walking on an uncomfortable flat surface. They are certainly what I would expect for the price - but the jury is still out on whether or not I will keep them. For me - I don't think so - I expected them to stand up a little bit above the knee. They do in fact go above the knee, but they HUG it, and that is not flattering on a shorter thicker leg like mine. I would have expected made in China, but a check of the website says it's founded in CA, so not quite sure where in fact they're manufactured. But they are definitely cheaply made, certainly as I expected for the price, but if the style was slightly more flattering and/or the smell goes away, I would consider keeping them. These are the kinds of boots you get that you don't expect to last more than one season, if that, but they stretch the wardrobe and you can potentially get a few pairs and have a few different styles w/o the major $$$. Maybe 1 of my nieces will like them, otherwise they will probably go back, but, I MIGHT try another style from this company if I think it will be more suitable. Do your feet a BIG FAVOR, definitely order a 1/2 size up to add a shoe insert.

UPDATE: DID RETURN THE BOOTS. They didn't fit any of my nieces (2 16's, 17, 20 & 21) & everyone acknowledged that the boots have an extremely narrow foot; & the smell did NOT go away for the few days we had them. If you are lucky enough for these to fit your feet/legs, then as I stated in my initial review, it's good to have as a wardrobe stretcher for certain outfits. They are not the greatest quality, as the odor immediately reveals, and they are not likely to last all that long. Woulda if I coulda! But no can do!nitial review, it's good to have as a wardrobe stretcher for certain outfits. column13: with a wide toe-box and just enough arch support to feel good - too much arch just hurts my feet
column14: I stand all day at work, have fallen arches, and my feet are a half-size apart. I need a shoe that is well padded, with a wide toe-box and just enough arch support to feel good - too much arch just hurts my feet. My shoes also have to be affordable, and I must avoid any with memory foam, as I've discovered that I have a sensitivity to it - really an allergic reaction. These shoes feature "yoga mat" soles, are the most comfortable I've found in years, and I can wear them all day without pinched toes or aching feet. I'd been hunting for a new work shoe since Easy Spirit redesigned my old stand-by style, and this is the one - I hope they're available for years to come. But just in case, I bought a few extra pairs.

column6: ASICS Women's GEL-Scram 2 Running Shoe
column14: Asics just don't agree with me, I suppose. These were the first Asics I kept and am regretting it terribly after walking outside on the trail. When I tested them at home they seemed fine, except for a gripping feel on the ankle even though the size was fine. After walking five miles one day and getting halfway through my walk the following day, the left sneaker began to painfully scrunch the little toes of my left foot. Shortly after, the top of my right foot under the shoe's tongue began to hurt terribly as if something was puncturing my bones. But I looked and nothing seemed to rub anywhere. I am guessing that the shoes were built to correct some foot issue that I do not have, thus making these a misery for me. Which is a shame as they do appear very well made and I don't believe the size was the issue. I have never had such discomfort to the point of hobbling before, and prior to this have been wearing a deteriorating pair of Avias, a far chintzier brand, now held together with band aids on the inside, which even in that condition are way, way more comfortable than the Asics. I don't get why everyone loves these. The comfort and support I was feeling at first quickly wore off and my feet hated them.

column13: These are comfortable, but very definitely not genuine shearling
column14: These are comfortable, but very definitely not genuine shearling. The tag attached to the sole of the slippers says, "Genuine Leather Upper / Lining: Real Dyed Shearling from Lamb 70% / Real Dyed Knitted Wool from Lamb 30% / Shearling Fur Origin: Australia / Knitted Wool Origin: Australia / Rubber Sole / Made in China / ACV-2014". However, all of the fur parts have a synthetic backing, so they are definitely not "genuine shearling" (i.e. not made from sheepskin with the fur attached). It's very easy to part the fibers and look down to see what they're attached to, and it ain't sheepskin. They are comfortable, but they may not wear well due to not being genuine shearling.

column6: Mizuno Women's Wave Inspire 11 Running Shoe
column13: The color of these is awesome and I get compliments all of the time
column14:
I purchased the Mizuno Paradox at the same time as these Mizuno Wave Inspire shoes, both to compare them and also to possibly use these ones for more every day wear. The color of these is awesome and I get compliments all of the time. It's why I decided to buy a second pair!
These are one step lower than the Paradox, but have similar support. They are very lightweight for a support shoe and are very comfortable. At this point I am not sure if the top of the shoe in the forefront area will be an issue for me, as it is a bit small or there seems to be a rigid piece of the shoe that may prove to be a deal-breaker but is doing okay as of now.
Wearing orthotics with this shoe you would have to get a larger size. There is no way it would fit. In addition, I am really feeling the pressure of the top of the shoe where the laces are tied. I have that problem in many shoes where my circulation suffers if it is too tight or presses against my foot wrong on the top nearest the ankle; however, I think buying a longer set of shoe laces and tying them as many runners do, I will add on to my review after I do that and after I go for a run in these. Love them!

column6: Ariat Men's Sport Wide Square-Toe Western Cowboy Boot
column14:
I bought these boots locally as I was concerned about the fit and I wanted to compare the comfort with several different brands. In every other shoe I own (athletic, dress, etc.) I wear a size 12D. In these boots a size 12D was very loose. I could squeeze into an 11D, but the toe box was a little tight on my left foot. The toe box on boots is rigid and doesn't wear in, so be careful of that. I went with an 11.5D and it fits great.

These boots were much more comfortable out of the box than the Justins that I tried on. I had really expected to need much more break in time to get them to feel that good. After a couple days of wear, they wore in and are now the most comfortable boots I have owned. Also, the quality of these boots in the stitching and materials seems to be much better than the price would suggest.

One thing that you will notice with square toe boots is that there are a lot of differences in widths between different boot styles and makers. I tried on several other pairs that seemed too wide in the toe. Many of the boots that brands designate as "work boots" tend to be wider and it detracts from the look of the boot in my opinion. These are not super-wide and look great while still being super comfortable in the toe.

Lastly, I went with the distressed leather version of this boot. They look really great with a pair of jeans. I tried the other styles of this boot as well as a few pair from Justin. Without a doubt, these in distressed leather were the best looking pair. I didn't want a pair of boots that looked like I was headed out to a Western bar, I wanted something that looked like I wore them every day (which I do). If you want a nice pair of boots that don't look like you are trying to play cowboy dress up, this is a solid choice.

column6: Montrail Women's Mountain Masochist II Trail Running Shoe
column13: These were amazing, got me through my first Warrior Dash, best sneaker I've ever worn
column14: I underpronate, have wide forefeet and very high arches, about a size 9 or so. Bought these for my first Warrior Dash last fall. AWESOME for that, and for regular street use too. The soles were extremely grippy, even on the Giant Cliffhanger which was slippery with mud from the prior obstacle and my biggest worry on the course. They cleaned off perfectly, and they had been soaked through and through with mud. Instant comfort, fit like a glove the first time wearing them, too. No break-in needed at all, a big shock. I bought maybe a halfsize too large (my size wasn't available but the reviews were just too good). Still the lacing design (those dark bands that extend down from the laces) allows me to tighten not just the laces but the entire uppers comfortably around my feet, but you'd never notice it just looking at them. I wish my size was still available or I'd get another pair today. Solid materials too: the uppers won't wear holes in them or fall apart ever, I don't think. Best shoe I've ever worn.

column6: Bates Men's Sport Comp Toe Uniform Work Boot
column13: Steel toecaps will be one size larger!  Order the next size smaller for your shoe size!
column14:
Adult Men's and Women's Shoe Size Conversion Table
https://niceshoes.ca/sizes?q=sizes&nojs=true

"... If they have a steel toecap, they will almost always be one size larger than a conventional fit. So for example, if you take a size 9 boot usually, you‚Äôll need a size 8. This isn‚Äôt always the case, but it‚Äôs true for around 95% of customers, and is only likely to be different if you have a very broad foot AND a very high instep!"

I am a size 8.5-9 on my large foot, and size 8.5 on my small foot. For me, these shoes were 1.5 over-sized for use in hot weather. Typically, I'll step into a 7.5-8 size boot, and a size 8.5 for sneakers/tennis shoes. (Absolutely no smaller in sneakers/tennis shoes, as my large foot big toe will easily protrude through the fine clothe.) In brief, I had to order a size 7 for these shoes. Even though they are not steel toe, they are still a composite safety toe shoe.

The main reason I purchased these, I was getting sick and tired of always buying tennis shoes every six months, which would easily and always wear-out or tear after only six months. Later I noticed the cloth of my sneakers simply drying-out after a very brief period, and then will tear easily. Hence, I'm back to leather! I've had a pair of similar style Corocan boots, which have lated 10 years with only some signs of ageing as of now.

I also purchased a pair of Bates Men's Hi Shine Uniform High Shine Oxford, for wearing with some Dickies 874 uniform polyester/cotton blend trousers instead of wearing Levis jeans, for which the jeans also wear and tear too easily. (The polyester/nylon blended trousers are suppose to wear better or wear-out less easily.)

PROS
1) Tennis/Sneaker shoe model, but in leather. This is a standard thick leathered shoe. No fine leather, or leather that will tear or wear too easy. (Other models have used fine leathers, with also customers complaining and likely not using Lexol regularly for those fine leathers.)
2) Almost as breathable as a tennis/sneaker shoe.
3) Almost as light like as a tennis/sneaker shoe. (Tennis/sneaker is ~11 5/8 - 12 ounces. These leather shoes are 17 1/4 ounces.)

CONS
1) Over-sized due to the safety (non-steel) comp toe. (The safety comp toe is usually standard with most leather boots.)
2) Not as light as tennis shoes, but having shoes with thin leather will likely wear-out or tear too easily. Due care is required of all leather, and the lighter the leather, the less forgiving leather is. Hence, if you do not wax or Lexol your shoes often, make sure you get thicker leather!
3) The arch is a little tight, but will likely wear-in as this is a thick leather shoe. As such, the arch is probably perfect, I just won't know this for a week or so, or sooner if in hot weather.

TIP: If you wear these in hot weather, you might want to step a half size smaller as there's likely no need for thick boot socks. (Hence, the reason why I went from a size 8.5 to a size 7, instead of a size 7 1/2 for these shoes.) Colder weather might require boot socks, hence requiring a little extra room for the thicker socks.hable as a tennis/sneaker shoe. 3) Almost as light like as a tennis/sneaker shoe. column13: Thick but plenty of organizational spots
column14:
As a clutch wallet goes, this one has a spot for just about everything. Photo id, credit cards, store cards, etc, there are plenty of spaces in two different areas. There is an interior zippered compartment for coins. And there are there separated places inside for for bills, receipts, etc. There is also an additional outside pocket (unsecured) for other slips of whatever. It closes with a snap (my version does). It is pretty heavy duty, almost to a fault. It is thick right out of the box, an inch and a quarter wide at the thickest part before putting anything in. So it only gets bulkier as you fill it. If you have a large bag and size isn't an option, it is comforting to have something with some girth. If you like a thinner, more compact clutch, I would try the other style that isn't so thick. The print on it is cool but unless there are different spellings from other countries, the clutch spells out Pacefic Ocean (instead of Pacific). Not a big deal but something I notice every time I look at it.

It is a wipeable vinyl with the print on most outer areas and a brown interior. Sample provided for review.

column6: Soda Womens Equity-S Padded Collar Ankle Lace Up Boot
column13: Cute and comfy - just SIZE UP!
column14: I love these boots for winter in NYC. I have been searching and searching for years for a lug sole suede like boot and did NOT want Timberland boots. I was looking to replace a pair of pink suede boots that look just like these and it took FOREVER to find them ( paid 3 times the price 10 years ago for those). I got these in my regular size, not paying attention to EVERY review that said to size up. I should have listened so I exchanged and sized up and they are perfect. And even with sizing up, they make my foot look teeny tiny! And now they are so comfortable. I don't find a problem with the arch support and the back is really nice and cushioned. I will spray with protective spray and quite frankly, at this price, I don't mind if they only last through one or 2 winters, I just wanted the look to wear with jeans and be cute and comfy.  You MUST size up in these but don't worry, your feet will thank you and still look cute and small! I got the cement color and I LOVE them.  The seller was great and the exchange was easy.  I am so pleased and can't wait for fall. I won't only wear them in bad weather, I will wear them with jeans and big oversized sweaters and make my outfit look cute.  I didn't want the look of Timberlands which is why I chose the cement color which is a great neutral and they give some lift and height (even though I'm 5'6").  I might even get a second pair just to have a back up since it took 10 years to find a cute back up to the pair I was looking to replace.  If you size up, I think you will like these. They are very cute and comfortable.

column6: Khombu Women's Rachel Walking Shoe
column13: For all of the poor shoes that now have to be compared to Sketchers....these included :O
column14:
When I snagged these on a lightning deal, I had high hopes they would be as good as my beloved Sketchers...Um...well.. Don't get me wrong...they aren't BAD, they just aren't GREAT.
What is good about them:
Stylish - They are a cute shoe. The woven material is different and has a nice stretch
Pretty comfortable - When you first put them on they do have that, "ahhhhh" factor which lulls you into thinking your feet will have the same reaction after several hours but...not so for me :( At the end of the day I had slightly achy feet - not like the pain from, oh..4 inch spike heels, but discomfort
Decent quality - Pretty well made although I notice that the black wedge sides are made from that type of material that, after some wear, looks like peeling skin from a sunburn. So far not bad, but then I've only worn them a few times. We'll see how they wear
Pretty cushy insole - Not like thick, memory foam of higher end shoes but decent. I still always tend to add a medium weight comfort insole to all of my shoes for extra support.
Sizing is a bit on the large side - I always order a half size up to be able to fit an extra insole and for room in the toe box but these ran big. I ended up having to exchange them for the next size down which fit perfect
All in all, these are a cute shoe, reasonable price, reasonable comfort but still don't hit the mark for an all day, happy feet Sketchers sort of experience.
I will keep them in spite of their short comings and wear them for shorter durations only because they are a bit dressier than the average casual shoe.

column6: Marc by Marc Jacobs Classic Q Baby Aidan Shoulder Bag
column14:
Been hunting for a handbag for a while, mainly considering a few styles from Louis Vuitton (LV). In the end, I can't see spending thousands on a handbag at this time. Marc Jacobs designed for LV for a while, so I decided to look into his line. After researching his handbags, I can definitely see his style reflected in his work with LV. This particular handbag is from a few seasons ago, but it has some of the design elements that I liked in a few of the LV bags, so I went with it.

Worth noting:
*Overall, I'm very satisfied - though, I wouldn't say this is an equal substitute for an actual LV bag (this is NOT why I took a star off, it is just an observation).

*Due to it's design, the base is wider than the top - resulting in an openning smaller than the base. Given this, I find myself having to feel around my bag to grab something that has made its way into the corners; bags of this shape will all suffer from this to a degree.

*It's what I call a "smooshy" bag, meaning it doesn't hold all of its structure like a stiffer bag would when set down. However, it doesn't deflate and go flat.

*A good sized "medium" bag. It's large enough for my essentials (umbrella, glasses w/ case, sunglasses, 2 small makeup bags, large wallet, large smart phone) with room for other items like a tablet (not laptop) and a water bottle.

Pro's
*Convertible bag - can be carried in hand or by strap. Strap can be removed.
*The leather is soft and textured.
*Handles - they're thick and I appreciate the rolled leather, which makes it comfortable to hold
*Hardware & zipper are sturdy. I like that is has feet as well.
*Pockets - 1 roomy zipper pocket and 2 open "tech" pockets.
*Details - I appreciate its pleating, branding on hardware, and other design details that give it character.

Con's
*The lining. It's very busy for me - I'd rather have it be a solid color (other than black).
*Zipper. It's not bad, but it can get hung up - which may be due to the nature of the bag than the zipper.
*Weight - this is not a feather weight bag when empty. Personally, I don't think it's too heavy, some might disagree.
*Crossbody - wearing it crossbody changes the bag's shape significantly on my long frame. It's a nice convenience in a pinch tho.her than black).
*Zipper. It's not bad, but it can get hung up - which may be due to the nature of the bag than the zipper.
*Weight - this is not a feather weight bag when empty. Personally, I don't think it's too heavy, some might disagree.
*Crossbody - wearing it crossbody changes the bag's shape significantly on my long frame. It's a nice convenience in a pinch tho.

column6: Nike Women's In Season TR 4 Cross Trainer Running Shoe
column13: Beautiful Look & Support but TOO TIGHT
column14: I loved the look and support of these shoes but had to send them back. I had the right size for my foot, but I do have high arches and this shoe just didn't leave me with enough room. The wrap style of the attached tongue means there is no room to adjust...so if you have high arches, this shoe probably won't work for you. Also, there was a LOT of pinching going on at the joint between my upper foot and my toes...the fabric changes over from being fully flexible to leather right at the bend point which was extremely painful when my foot flexed at all - walking, standing on toes, etc. They definitely could & should have softened that seem for comfort. It's a very pretty shoe with good support, though. For someone with flat, skinny feet - these would be a real gem!

column13: I don't like this new way of making sneakers, not for high arches
column14: These sneakers are probably right on as far as size goes, they do fit as far as width and length, my toes have wiggle room and the shoes aren't too narrow. They don't really fit my feet though. What bothers me is that the tongue is one piece with the shoe, there isn't an opening going down both sides like you would find in older sneakers, it's kind of like a slip-on shoe but with laces over the top. I've noticed this with my daughters Nike's too so I know it's not just a Puma thing. For me this doesn't really work, I have high arches and with a loose tongue I can accommodate my arches by lacing the shoe a little looser towards the top. With these I feel like I'm cramming my foot in and it hurts the top of my foot. I do like the design, the grey with pink accents is cute and they are a nice simple shoe, that's exactly what I wanted. I have worn these out so I can't return them, I thought they might stretch after wearing them but they haven't. I am back to looking for another pair, I just wish that the descriptions would disclose that the tongue is sewn closed. The only other thing that I can think of is maybe cutting the tongue down the side to give me the room I need. I still rated these highly because I think the shoes are good overall. I'm not sure many people will have the same problem that I do, just be warned if you have high arches.

column14: I love these shoes. They are the most comfortable shoes I've ever worn.  Which is surprising, because I have extremely high arches and these shoes provide no arch support whatsoever. Also, I really like a shoe that has a little more height in the heel/sole because I'm only 5' tall and I have trouble reaching lots of things.  So I'm trying to wean myself off of them and find shoes that are a little taller and offer more support.  But they are soft as butter inside and out.  They've also been subject to drenching rainstorm puddles and enchilada sauce accidents to no ill effect.  They can be wiped off quickly with a damp cloth (or dried overnight) and are good to go. Even with very recently purchased sunglasses developing a lens defect or any kind of defect, I did not see a single case of Oakley repairing free. column6: Mizuno Men's Wave Enigma 5 Running Shoe
column13: Previously an Asics Devotee, I'm Loving These Mizunos!
column14:
I have high arches and have long been loyal to Asics, both for running and for casual tennis shoes. I never had any reason to try another brand, until Amazon Vine presented the opportunity for me to try these awesome Mizuno Wave Enigma 5 shoes for free. "BLOWN AWAY" are two words that best summarize my experience so far with these shoes.

**POSITIVES**

+ Style/Appearance: My Asics aren't much for beauty contests, but these Mizunos are lookers, for sure. I love the metallic blue trim, as well as the yellow midsole. Of course, you'll love the color coordinated laces that you will, unfortunately, never find again when time to replace.

+ Comfort Beyond Compare: I cannot tell a lie. These are more comfortable than any other running shoe I have ever worn. They are amazing--ample arch support, incredibly soft cushioning, snug but not tight fit, super soft tongue, somewhat stretchy/elastic laces, supple/luxurious sock liner (could wear barefoot!), and perfect width for normal feet (no too wide or too narrow areas).

+ Excellent Breathability: I've worn these for extended periods in warm weather, and the cooling from the breathable mesh material is outstanding. I've never had the urge to get them off because they are too hot, and I am the kind of guy who is always taking off his shoes.

**UNSURE/NEGATIVES**
It's truly difficult to nitpick on these shoes. In the early going, they seem virtually flawless, but here's my attempt at finding fault.

- Yellow Midsole Difficult to Clean: These shoes are so beautiful that you'll find yourself trying to keep them pristine. I have the nasty habit of using one shoe to kick off the other by placing the toe of one shoe on the heel of the other. DOH! I dirtied up the bright yellow midsole, and I was so bummed, especially since I could not get it clean with a wet rag. Perhaps I will try a mild detergent, but the typical wet rag isn't doing it.

- Extra Laces Please: I know it isn't industry practice, but when you are paying for top-of-the-line running shoes (I got to try these for free, to be clear), it doesn't seem like too much to ask for an extra pair of the perfectly coordinated laces to be in the box. These laces are to die for, both in color match and in performance with their stretchy/elastic feel.

- Somewhat Long Laces: I haven't used the extra ankle-tightening laces hole eyelets at the very top yet, which would help, but these laces do seem quite long. With their stretchiness, I found that I needed to have really big loops when I tied them at the top in order to avoid my laces hitting the ground. Not a huge deal, but I am trying to nitpick virtually perfect shoes!

Durability will be tested with possible future updates to this review, as I have less than a month on these. So far, they are holding up wonderfully.

Overall, it's tough not to LOVE these shoes, and love them I do. Trying is believing. I never expected I'd be won over, given my past loyalty to Asics.s Please: I know it isn't industry practice, but when you are paying for top-of-the-line running shoes (I got to try these for free, to be clear), it doesn't seem like too much to ask for an extra pair of the perfectly coordinated laces to be in the box. column13: I Love Sperry; This Particular Pair Stained my Socks (see below)
column14:
A note on Sperrys, at least in my experience: breaking them in is a bloody experience. Get some padding for whatever part(s) of your foot they start to irritate, or wear thick socks for the first few times. I've been breaking these guys in and my heels have cuts on them because I was wearing low-rise socks, haha. This is my second pair and I've had issues with both. After a week, they're damn comfortable and last for years.

The blood isn't even the reason I'm giving these guys four-stars instead of five. The trouble is that the insole of the shoe (it's a dark/medium blue) stained my white socks. I'm sure this is 100% similar to what happens with new denim jeans. Sperry TS should find a way to wear out the insole before putting it in the shoe. Beyond that, this is a great sperry. It's pure white (don't get the 'Ice,' if you want 'White.' Get 'White')

column6: Bates Men's High Shine Duty Work Shoe
column13: Apparently sized according to safety toe and maybe be one size larger! Likely order the next size smaller for your shoe size.
column14:
Although these shoes are not advertised as having a safety composite toe, I can see some characteristics of this shoe having some sort of minimal safety composite toe. As such, shoe sizing likely will be considered according to the following:

Adult Men's and Women's Shoe Size Conversion Table
https://niceshoes.ca/sizes?q=sizes&nojs=true

"... If they have a steel toecap, they will almost always be one size larger than a conventional fit. So for example, if you take a size 9 boot usually, you‚Äôll need a size 8. This isn‚Äôt always the case, but it‚Äôs true for around 95% of customers, and is only likely to be different if you have a very broad foot AND a very high instep!"

I am a size 8.5-9 on my large foot, and size 8.5 on my small foot. For me, these shoes were at least one size over-sized for use in hot to mildly cold weather. (ie. Light dress socks) Typically, I'll step into a 7.5-8 size boot, size 8 dress shoe, and a size 8.5 for sneakers/tennis shoes. (Absolutely no smaller in sneakers/tennis shoes, as my large foot big toe will easily protrude through the fine clothe.) In brief, I had to order a size 7 for these shoes.

PROS
1) Good standard dress oxford shoe.
2) I love the soles, as they provide good cushion as well as good traction!
3) Does not requiring constant care. (These shoes seem to have a vinyl coated leather? You'll apparently see vinyl coated leather used for leather vehicle seats.)

CONS
1) Although apparently properly sized now at a size 7M and I do not think I require a size 7 wide, they're still a little uncomfortable for continuous walking. In other words, they're not like jogging or running shoes. Updated several weeks later, these shoes are more comfortable now after inserting a very cheap inner sole below the original sole. Also, just using Lexol and wearing regular cotton socks for the past weeks has also seemed to help break these shoes in... or my feet. Likely just the sole needs to break in just right for parts of the foot to not rub against parts of the upper shoe?
2) A pair of Allen Edmonds shoes may still be more comfortable?

TIP: If these are vinyl coated leather shoes, from my research on the Internet, they still need leather cleaner, leather conditioner and shoe polish/wax. People have stated the conditioner will eventually absorb, as vinyl coated leather is still somewhat porous.

TIP: The composite toe and heal can be further broken in by manually creasing the material with your hands.foot to not rub against parts of the upper shoe? 2) A pair of Allen Edmonds shoes may still be more comfortable? People have stated the conditioner will eventually absorb, as vinyl coated leather is still somewhat porous. TIP: The composite toe and heal can be further broken in by manually creasing the material with your hands.

I was able to hammer the heel back on, but really, should I have to do that?  I have worn them several more times since then.  When it comes time to removing them, I now loosen the laces first.  It is a little more of a problem since I ladder-lace them, but the heel at least has remained on.  The boot leather is soft and pliable.  Try not to wear them in bad weather though.  These shoes are not meant for rugged wear.

column13: 5 because it would be better to have slightly smaller than to have slightly bigger ...
column14:
This is a late review.. but here it is:

I ordered size 8, but they contacted me a few days later to tell me that they do not have size 8 anymore. I usually wear size 7.5 to 8.5 so I went with 7.5 instead of 8.5 because it would be better to have slightly smaller than to have slightly bigger size of running shoes. When I got the product, I realized it isn't the right size for me. I wish I could have just canceled the order when they told me they didn't have the right size. The shoe soles were way thin/light for me, and it honestly feels like wearing a sock shaped of a shoe. I don't wear this anymore, but I mean.. if I didn't have my other Nike sneakers that I bought after this order, I would wear this for emergency purposes (as in working out, not actual emergency) or jobs that would get my sneakers wet/dirty (rowing). FYI, the black part is a mesh-like material, so it kind of shines.

This is just my personal opinion, so don't feel like this wouldn't be a good product for you; if you like lightweight sneakers and have narrow feet, go for it dude.

column6: Mizuno Men's Wave Inspire 11 Running Shoe
column14:
I've been a Mizuno fan for the last several years after switching from Brooks because they were giving me knee pain. Recent studies suggest that the best way to choose a shoe is to simply find one that fits your foot and that you find comfortable. The Wave Inspire is that shoe for me--I have slightly narrow feet and the shoe fits perfectly. It also gives enough cushion without being too cushioned. I pronate a bit (not extreme) and the shoe handles that, well, in stride (sorry could not resist the terrible pun).

My only compliant with this shoe (and Mizuno shoes in general) is that the soles seem to wear faster than other brands.

column6: Prince Men's Viper VII Mid Tennis Shoe
column13: The only \mid\" tennis shoe that works for me"
column14:
As others mention, there are few "mid" tennis shoe options out there. These are my third or fourth pair of mid Vipers (various generations). These accommodate my orthotics AND have the wide toe box I need. Nothing else works for me. I wish they were more aesthetically pleasing (the trend seems to be they are getting worse, not better). I suspect Prince does not feel they sell in enough volume to justify a second color scheme--and that they keep the styling conservative because the average age of wearers is 35/40/45+?

I've worn them about a year; recreational play on hard courts once or twice a week. I think I'm about ready for another pair, as the tread is getting pretty worn on left shoe from dragging my toes.

I pair these with thick Thor-Lo socks.

[Side note: I exchanged emails with people at Prince corporate as I waited for this current model to come out--my old ones were very worn and I was growing anxious they had discontinued the Viper. It was a long wait, but they did finally release this Viper VII (out of a new factory, which was part of the delay). I was impressed by the quick response of the corporate rep.]

column6: Scarpa Men's Spark Trail Running Shoe
column13: Great Fit, Decent Cushion, 300 mile lifespan
column14: Can't believe I got these shoes for only $60! Best-fitting trail shoes I've ever had. Nice, big toe box, without it being ridiculously over-sized like Altras. Stable, comfortable. Did two 20+ mile trail races in these, plus lots of long, rocky training runs, and never any blisters or problems. Cushioning is decent, but you can still definitely "feel the trail", and in fact, I'm now running in Scarpa Ignites, because I wanted a bit more cushion. One criticism is that they didn't last very long--started to fall apart around 275 miles (stitching on side) and then a big gash on the bottom forced me to retire them at 300 miles. Was hoping to get at least 100 more miles out of them. Love the Ignites so far, and will review them after I see how long they hold up.

column14:
Great purse! I read the reviews before I purchased, and had this in my 'wish list' for quite a while before I took the plunge.

I know they provide measurements, but I was looking at the picture of the dummy with it, and expected a larger purse-- read the measurements!! column14:
COMFORT and SUPPORT: The insole is memory foam, which I'm not sure is the best choice of material for a shoe insole -- It didn't feel very cushioning. The arch support is so-so for my high arches: It only supports the outer arch, while the inner part of my arch and metatarsal do not have any support. All in all, this shoe was not comfortable enough to keep, despite the low price.

FIT: I am usually between 6.5 and 7, and my foot measures between 9 and 1/8 and 9 and 1/4 inches long. The ball of my foot is somewhat wide. I chose the size 7, and it was just right in length.

These would be fine for someone with slightly lower arches or flatter feet, as well as narrower feet.

column13: These look great, however in the medical/dental field I am on ...
column14:
These look great, however in the medical/dental field I am on my feet and running around a good amount of time throughout my 10+ hour days. These shoes are SO incredibly uncomfortable and do not flex at all, even with trying to break them in prior to use at work! I have BRUISES on top of my feet where these sit!!! They are stubborn as all heck and won't hardly budge or flex when walking. Also, the bottom broke apart by the toe (mind you I wore these LESS than 5 hours). I could get about an hour in these shoes and had to constantly be taking them off throughout the day. They would be quite comfortable if I could just get past how stiff they are. Would not recommend, or if you want to spend forever trying to break these in I would go a size bigger. Save yourself from being in so much pain!

Update: I have had these maybe a little over a month and they have hardly broken in. I have tried breaking them in and wearing them around the house before and on my feet over 10 hours a day they're still stiff. I have permanent numbness on the tops of my feet where they lay. They are also cracking on the tops AND the bottoms have fallen apart. Would not recommend, especially in the medical or dental field

I always wear the same size in New Balance athletic shoes but that size in this shoe feels different -- as earlier mentioned by others, the toe box feels smaller/shorter (and I wear a Wide fit). The liner could provide more arch support but that I'll fix with new arch supports when the liners in these wear out.  Nice and light, great cushioning. column13: I will never take these off again!
column14:
Crocs seems to continuously make great products. The texture of the shoe gel has always had a nice sponge-like feel. When I first bought these flip flops for the sake of having them, I was a bit surprised how stiff they felt. It didn't seem to have the ordinary crocs feel, but I gave it a shot and tried it out.

I was surprised how addictive they felt. Just like most crocs, the tiny stitching on the bottom have nice stimulus to the bottoms of my soles, and made my feet feel they were not wearing anything, while protecting normally weary and calloused feet. Have been doing more Fitbit steps than I ever imagined wearing these slippers. I had a heel blister from wearing sneakers several days ago, so was forced to use these flip flops even more.Yesterday I went 66000 steps and could've went more if I had a little more time in the day. I swear by these. I have never comfortably put up Fitbit numbers like the ones I am getting without these slippers! Forget running sneakers, I will be running a marathon in these!!!

column14: These are the cutest shoes ever. I bought them for my son and in the football print because football season is starting soon and besides, brown is a nice neutral color in general. I received them quickly and was pleasantly surprised with the packaging. It comes in it's own box so gifting would be a breeze. Looking at the shoes, they look well made. I don't think it will break with normal wear and tear. Although it is not real leather, the material is soft. I like how the inside of the shoe is terry lined. That means no socks are needed and the terry will absorb any sweat. The terry means it's also going to be soft against your baby's foot. The side panels stretch so you can easily put baby's foot in the shoe. I bought them in size 9-12 months and they fit my baby's foot good and he'll be turning 11 months next week. The bottom sole is rubber, I initially thought it was plastic but it's actually rubber. This is good news as my child can wear these shoes on carpet, tile, wood, and any other surface and I don't have to worry about him slipping. I am so impressed with these shoes that I a going to purchase another pair in green (the zebra design). I received this product at a discounted price in exchange for an unbiased review.

column6: Ahnu Women's Sugarpine Air Mesh Hiking Shoe
column13: Over 5 days we hiked about 40 miles on pretty challenging terrain
column14: I bought these as my first pair of hiking shoes for a camping trip that I went on last month. Over 5 days we hiked about 40 miles on pretty challenging terrain, and they handled it really well for the most part. The soles of the shoes did not have very good traction on wet rocks or gravel, but they were good otherwise. They're very comfortable, but I would recommend either long thick socks, or forgoing these for the waterproof boots. These were not very waterproof (didn't realize I had ordered the mesh ones) and although they were comfy I got blisters on both heels even from short hikes because of the height of the backs of the shoes. Despite this, I think these shoes are a decent option, especially for the price.

column6: Salomon Men's Sense Pro Shoes
column13: My least favorite Salomon shoe yet.
column14: I am a huge Solomon fan. I have had seven pairs from the Sense Ultra 3s to the Fellraisers and even the Quest 4D GTX boots. I bought the Sense Pro because Solomon says it was based off of the Sense Ultra 3 S-labs but they were made for more of the urban to trail type stuff. I am away from the trails for a couple months so this seemed like a good fit.... Nope, the shoe looks the same but that is about where things end. My major complaint with this shoe is high heel to toe. Coming from the Ultra 3s or a fore foot running shoe these things feel like sketchers. Next the race lace pocket falls under the laces when tightened making it a chore to fit the loose end into the pocket. The lace eyes are already fraying. column6: KEEN Utility Men's Pittsburgh Soft Toe Work Boot
column14:
First Impression- After a week of wear, I love these boots. Very quick break-in, and very comfortable out of the box. In the first week I have soaked them in water, trudged through concrete slurry while pouring a foundation, walked several miles, and have worked in rainy weather as well as hot, sunny weather. My feet feel great at the end of the day...not too hot and never wet (socks are moist from sweat, but not soaked).They feel like a hiking boot, allow for a natural stride on account of the perfect flex point in the shank and built in toe rocker, the tread is excellent and grips very well on a variety of surfaces, the lacing system is effective and efficient, and the Keen-dry membrane is waterproof and very breathable. Build quality is excellent.

Other reviewers have mentioned the overly padded tongue, but I don't find it to be thicker than the tongue on other boots I have owned. I can't speak on durability, but if the longevity of my last pair of Keen shoes are any indication of the durabilty of these boots, I expect a good year of hard wear out of them. I am a building contractor and wear my boots all day, every day. I will update after a few months of wear.

I've seen reviews on line that some Dansko clogs have problems with crumbling soles, but this is the cork (or "cork-like") material. They are now unwearable. I would expect Danskos to last for YEARS. column13: Too Big, and Not Allowed to Exchange for Proper Size at Original Purchase Price
column14: When I received this pair of Stacy Adams shoes I was pretty excited. They looked great, and, having wanted to buy a pair of this brand for a while, I bought them because they were at a great price. Unfortunately, as other reviews had mentioned, they can run a bit large. This pair was about 1 size too big. I wear an 11 in both shoes and sneakers, but even accounting for the longish style they were way too big for me. The real problem came when I went to exchange them for a smaller size; in order to do that, I was directed to buy the same style at more than double the price! I had hoped to try this one pair and, if they were suitably comfortable and wore well, to start buying different styles. When I found the price hike on this style, I had identified another style of Stacy Adams shoes at a similarly low price, and was going to order that one in a size 10, having saved it in my cart. Yet when I got the refund notice for the return of this too large pair, I went to order the other style and found that the price on that other pair was also hiked, again to more than double what I was planning to pay. So much for that trial run.

column13: Good boots but don't last as long as expected
column14:
I purchased these boots about a year ago, I tried them on in a local big name retailer and found them $20 cheaper on Amazon. The boots were amazingly comfortable, seemed well constructed and looked great. First couple days were tough as is with most boots but after the initial break in period they felt great. I typically work a 9 hour day and had no issues until about 6 months in.
The right boot sole started to come loose at the back a little. No big deal I just noticed it when I stepped, didn't affect performance. Few weeks later the laces wore out so I replaced them. Couple weeks after that I noticed I was getting wet feet - and I mean soaking wet. Even when it wasn't raining. I took a look at the sole and there was an approx 1 inch hole. I had to throw them away after about 8 months of use.

I had expected when I bought these to get at least a years worth of good use out of the boots. I'm not particularly hard on them, I work maintenance at an apartment complex. Trying a more expensive boot this time and we'll see how it goes

column6: New Balance Men's M750 Athletic Running Shoe
column13: Like running on baby angel kisses!
column14: These shoes are a dream. Light weight for distance running without being weighed down. Supportive and durable outsoles hold up against strong hard strides yet cushion every blow to fight off shin splints and save ur ankles. As if that isn't enough, the memory foam insole makes ur foot feel like it's been swallowed by a cloud. Many seem to feel there is less height in the heel portion of the shoe, whereas most running shoes have quite a difference in height ratio from the heel to the toe. However, to call these shoes flat runners is way off the mark. Yea there is slightly less height in the heel compared to other runners ive used, but the slight decrease in heel height actually seems to relieve the strain on the calf muscles. I recommend this shoe to everyone from beginners to crafted runners except for trail runners, just cuz there's not a great deal of support against lateral ankle movements that happen when u hit the dips and divots on a wooded trail. U'd  probably be better off with some cross trainers. Other than that, best shoe I've ever use for street running. Now stop wasting time reading the reviews, order the shoes and get ur lazy butt out there for a few miles!!! Game face!!!

column6: Fabuxry Women's Shoulder Bags Casual Handbag Travel Bag Messenger Cross Body Nylon Bags
column14: I wasn't sure if I was going to like this pocketbook or not--it was a choice between this one and another one I ordered. One was to be for me and one was to be a gift for my elderly aunt. In the end I decided to let my aunt choose which one she liked the best for her birthday. I am a pocket person, weather it is a pocketbook or weather it is with the clothes that I wear, so I wanted a pocketbook with a lot of pockets. And this one fits that perfectly! In fact, it had so many outside pockets that I did not discover all of them right away. I wanted multiple pockets so that I could organize and hold different things but at the same time allow me to put my hands right away on what I was searching for. These are some of the things I would carry around with me: My Kindle, my cell phone (basic), my clutch wallet, my wide tooth comb and a brush, paper and pen for when I needed to jot something down, something to hold change in, my lip gloss, cigarettes/lighter and my credit card holder/wallet type. At first I kept changing things around trying to figure out where I wanted to store things on the outside. Naturally the Kindle went into the back where the very wide pocket was, I finally put my basic cell phone in one of the pockets on the side, beneath where the straps are. There are 2 of those, one on each side. My credit card holder went into the pocket with the buckle on it, my cigarettes/lighter went into the Velcroed pocket next to the buckle pocket, and to my surprise, there was a small zipper pocket right behind the Velcro pocket, and even another pocket behind the zippered pocket. There was only one pocket inside the interior and I put my loose change there. The interior held everything else with room to spare. As much as this pocketbook held, it still was not too awkward and big to carry. It fit nicely on my shoulder and I had no trouble keeping it there. Oh, one thing I didn't discover for a few days, the large interior of the pocketbook has 2 zippers--that meet in the middle. I didn't realize this at first and was only using one zipper to zip it closed. I like the idea that if the pocketbook were to accidentally turn over then everything would be closed and could not spill out.  I have not had the pocketbook for long so I can't testify how long it will hold up--how long it will last. I hope it lasts a long time because I really like this pocketbook!he middle. column6: Bungalow 360 Large Messenger Bag (Alpaca)
column14:
I ordered this bag in two patterns; "alpaca" and "cow."

First, the good:
This bag is the perfect size for me. I love the canvas material, and I love all of the fun patterns that it is available in. It feels like it is of high quality and it will last me a good while. I also ordered matching wallets to go with each bag, and they are exactly what I had hoped they would be. I truly do love this bag, which brings me to...

The bad:
The alpaca print bag arrived wrapped in cellophane, and when I opened it, the bag gave off this overwhelming musty smell, as if it had been sitting in someone's damp basement for the last three years. Despite this, I transferred the contents of my old purse into the alpaca print purse yesterday afternoon, spritzed the purse with vinegar, and went to an outdoor event for several hours, hoping that the bag would naturally air itself out. No luck. This morning I emptied the bag, sprayed it inside and out with Febreze, and it is currently hanging outside on a tree. I will update this review if I ever get the smell to go away.

I had been looking forward to using the alpaca print bag the most because I have alpacas, and they look exactly like two of our guys. If I can't get rid of the smell, I won't use the purse. I feel embarrassed bringing it around people because it smells so strong. Fortunately, the cow print bag has only a faint smell to it that I think will go away fairly easily (and may have just originated from being shipped in the same box as the alpaca purse).

I would have given this bag five stars, if not for that unfortunate odor. The bag itself suits my needs perfectly, and I love the way it looks and feels slung over my shoulder.

EDIT (four days later): In addition to spraying the alpaca bag with vinegar and Febreze, I also tried washing it in the machine on gentle cycle with a pleasant-smelling detergent, and then hung the bag outside again for several more hours in the direct sunlight. I could STILL smell the horrible (mildew?) smell under all of the other scents on the bag. I have contacted the seller and will be returning this one.

As far as the cow bag goes, I hung it up for a couple of hours inside my house with the windows open, and that was enough to eliminate any odor that had spread from the alpaca bag onto it. The cow bag smells just like any normal, new purse.re hours in the direct sunlight. I could STILL smell the horrible (mildew?) smell under all of the other scents on the bag. I have contacted the seller and will be returning this one.

As far as the cow bag goes, I hung it up for a couple of hours inside my house with the windows open, and that was enough to eliminate any odor that had spread from the alpaca bag onto it. The cow bag smells just like any normal, new purse.

column6: Tommy Hilfiger Women's Renegade Rainboot
column14:
Oh man these are the best! I usually wear a size 8 1/2, or a 9 'medium width' if I get boots, but I ordered a size 8 and very glad I did. They do run a bit large just like the other reviewers said. For me, they are still easy to slip on and off with wool socks for a size 8 (and I have 'bigger' calf/ankles so that gives you an idea). Yet, they are aren't too big when walking around once they're on your feeties. In fact, they are so easy to slip on, that I'm wondering why it came with laces? I guess the laces are just for looks. But anyway, go with a size 8 if your about my size, and you won't regret it. I think the only thing to note, is that the interior of the boot isn't fabric, but another type of rubber that just has that 'plaid' painted look to it. I ordered the black with the red 'plaid' interior, and thought it'd be fabric, but oh well, I guess I didn't read the entire description so that's my fault. I'm actually GLAD it's not fabric on the inside, though. Being rain boots and all, if the inside ever got damp, then well...it'd get pretty smelly and gross with fabric. So good on them for not putting a fabric material on the inside. But, make sure you are wearing socks when you slip these on!

UPDATE 2016!
I still LOVE these so much. I don't have any rips or holes in my and almost wear them at least once a day (not a work though, lol). They are more of a 'rain' boot, but personally, I've been wearing them in the snow, too. They work just fine! Put on some cozy socks, and you'll love these. I wore these to my trip to England and soooo glad I had these (rain, rain, RAIN! Mud, and more mud, then more rain) and I also wore them on my flight to and from the States. Easy to slip off and put under the airplane seats (don't worry, I put on slippers so my feet don't stink up the place lol) and just a very versatile, useful boot :) Oh and yes, I get compliments on these babies.

column14:

column6: FRYE Women's Lucinda Slouch
column13: 5 Stars for the product - 1 star for the shipping (on this order only)
column14:
I got these for my lady who's been wanting these for a looooooong time so it's nice to have been able to move it from my wish list and buy them for her. She's never owned a pair of FRYE's (I've never even heard of them) and so she was VERY ecstatic that I got them for her as a surprise.

She's had foot surgery and pretty much had to stop wearing high heels and has finally worked her way up to 3 inches and so since she just had a garage sale and sold a lot of shoes that (even brand new ones) she can't wear and so luckily I had already ordered these and had it gift-wrapped and told her she got a Christmas present early.

Well, let's just say that she almost was brought to tears when she saw that they were ACTUALLY boots inside the shoebox instead of something else (I've been known to play pranks and put something different inside of an expensive box). And she kept asking me, "How did you know?!?" because she completely forgot she put those on my wishlist some time ago. Needless to say, even though it's summer she's ready to wear these NOW!!

So fellas, if you want to get a Birthday/Anniversary/Christmas present, this would be a 'step' in the right direction! Ha!

Now, on another note, the only CON to the whole thing.

The shipping box it came in (standard Amazon brown-box) had an issue: the top of the box was OPENED, as if someone had opened it up to see what was inside, found out it was gift-wrapped, and then put it back in and LAZILY put a clear piece of tape over the top that a 1yr old could've ripped off with out any effort.

Now, I live in a decent neighborhood on a dead-end street, and the box was left on the front porch like so many others have been, and to see what's on my porch, you have to LOOK on purpose to see what's up there or otherwise even walking you'd pass my porch rather quickly being it's recessed from the street and my house sits on a small hill elevated from the street.

So, unfortunately I'll never know why it was like that but fortunately it wasn't stolen or damaged because me and Amazon would've have some words to discuss.

I was tempted to take a picture and send it in, but being this is the first time that this has happened and that everything was in order, I was in a forgiving mood. If it happens again best believe I'll let the world know.

If anyone has any questions, comments or otherwise I'll be more than happy to answer them to the best of my ability.

column13: For the love of Achilles, do not buy these

Well, he's the culprit.  The edge is done in such a way that it cuts into your Achilles, most heinously.  I had to buy heel pads to thicken the back of the shoe, just below the edge, so it would push my foot forward and away from the Achilles wrecker.  The thing is, once you've got to go to such measures to make a shoe the least bit tolerable, it changes the way the rest of the shoe fits, which is less than ideal.  It's not comfortable enough to go for walks, so it ended up becoming my gardening shoe... and let me be clear here, I don't garden much.

column6: KEEN Women's Whisper Leather Sandal
column13: Can't seem to find a size that fits correctly, but they have a great look.
column14: I have been wearing Keens for years, but always the fabric strap/rubber sole kind. When I saw that Keens now come in this leather design, I was psyched. I actually had on my previous Keens while I was making the online order, so I checked the size and ordered that size (9). For context: I wear a 9 in almost all footwear, besides a few athletic shoes (Puma and Nike), in which I wear a 9.5. When these Keens arrived, I loved their look, but my heel hung off the back considerably, and I couldn't make them work at all. I also felt like even with wiggling my toes and tightening the straps of the shoe, I couldn't get my toes to a place where they stayed toward the front of the shoe as I walked (and therefore contributing to my heel hanging so far off the back). I was confused, but figured this style just ran small, and exchanged them for the 9.5. When the 9.5 arrived, my heel hung off the back of the shoe maybe slightly less, but still too much that it affected the comfort and aesthetic of my foot in the shoe (with every step I took, I could not only see but also feel that something was off and my heel was too far back). I put in an exchange for the 10 (even though I have never worn a size 10 in any shoe, ever), but I think the problem might be the shoe. Unlike the previous Keens that I have owned (the Whisper Sandal in fabric), the heel bed of this shoe is totally flat, rather than with a slight curve upwards at the back of the heel. That slight curve in the Keens I currently wear seems to function to keep my toes toward the front of the shoe and, overall, keep my foot in the right place. I think the problem with these Keens is that the heel bed is completely flat, with no curve at the back, so there is nothing to keep my toes toward the front of the shoe. I think the problem with the 10s will be that there is way too much space between my toes and the front of the shoe, but I'm still willing to give them a try -- I really like the way Keens look in leather!

column13: If you love animals please do not buy this.
column14: I would never buy this product and I ask you to also not buy it or any other product containing wool or sheepskin.  The sheep used to make wool are always abused horribly, even by so-called "sustainable"  farms.  They are skinned, and cut up alive, including the baby lambs.  And this is done in front of all the other lambs and sheep.  The horror, sadness and despair they experience cannot be put into words.  Please go to peta or any other compassionate animal groups' websites to see for yourself.. I try to spread the message but I cannot do it alone.  Please take a moment to copy this message and post it or something similar on any page where wool is sold..  Please never buy anything product containing wool. There are  many compassionate alternatives. and please help me spread the word. Thank you.

column14: A warm Croc. A good alternative to my other indoor winter slip-on shoes, the Halflinger clogs I had for over ten years. Halflingers are still great. But for people who aren't considerably well-to-do, this is an excellent alternative. It is high enough for people with high insteps, and wide enough for people who need or like wide shoes. Too many shoes lack this. Especially the high enough instep. You "Others": We've had it with trying to squeeze our instep into your flat-footed shoes!  Give it some -- even teensy -- bit of arch support, so my arch actually feels shoe underneath it instead of air, and I'll give it 5 stars.  Even though it is noticeably less "cushy" than my regular Croc from 2009. I don't know if the quality went down with cutting corners, or what. They're both good, but the difference in cushioned feel is sharply noticeable.

column14:

I live in California so I can often wear my sandals every day, all day....sometimes with socks. I now own four pair and am trying to decide on the next color to order! I still wear my first pair as it shows very little wear! Can't find that often in a shoe after 8 years!
I broke my left foot, ankle and leg about 2 1/2 years ago and can walk all day in these sandals. I only wear 3 brands of shoes Teva (Tirra), Keens and SAS shoes. I dress for style and comfort and these shoes accommodate me completely! I own more Teva sandals than any other brand. I recently went to the Santa Cruz Boardwalk and was on my feet from 10:30 am til 11:30pm, I only sat down when eating or riding rides. Thank you Teva for making a grand sandal that is stylish, pretty and ever so comfortable and colorful!!

column13: Love these shoes - but do not protect big toes
column14: I love these shoes.  The leather is very soft, it's very easy to put on by a 2 year old, and very light.  I bought one in 8, and they were a little too big for my son (he is a 7.5 Wide).  So I kept the 8 and bought the 7.  The 7 fits very well on him.  Just FYI - my son has chunky feet with high arch so it's a bit hard to find shoes that fit him perfectly.  We have been lucky with this particular See Kai Run.  My only complaint is that the shoes do not protect his big toe.  The opening on the front is big enough for his big toes to poke out.  I have noticed that his big toenails get chipped quite a bit.  I am guessing it is due to the fact that these shoes do not offer protection on the toes (unlike other brands like Keen).  I've been trying to think of ways to "cover" that hole, from ductaping it (which will probably make it look really ghetto), or to sewing a strip of leather to the shoes.  If any of the readers have any ideas, I'm open!  However, he has no complaints.  If I ask him to pick which shoes he wants to wear, he would pick these over and over again.  And these are perfect for summer, very airy and light.

column6: Mizuno Women's Wave Paradox Running Shoe
column13: Worth every penny and great for over-pronators!
column14:
I over-pronate and need the most stability and correction I can get, so I decided to try the Mizuno brand for the very first time. The Paradox are touted as the most stable within the Mizuno line and one step higher than the Wave Inspire I bought at the same time.
In a nutshell:
Stability: The stability is above average and I think will do quite well to correct my pronation. Even though it has been about a year since I wore my previous brand of stability enhancing shoes, my feet are not sore and I have been happy with how they are fitting and holding up so far.
Fit/Weight: Paradox are much lighter than my previous Asics, which is what I was looking for. Over-pronation correcting shoes are often heavy so these are nice on that front. The fit is neither too small or too roomy...they fit exactly to size. I would increase a 1/2-1 whole size larger if I needed to put my orthotics into them, though.
Comfort: I think support is the most important, but they are comfortable, as well. I'm surprised my feet are not hurting terribly while breaking them in, but so far, so good. I haven't taken a run in them yet though, so I may add on to this review once I accomplish that one.
Look: The disappointing thing with these shoes is probably the lack of colors to choose from, but they are quality shoes and this particular pair were incredibly affordable. I purchased the Wave Inspire at the same time so I could try them both out, and the colors were MUCH better, but the cost of the Wave Inspires was almost three times more than this sale price. All in all, I am extremely happy with my purchase!

column13: A WORKHORSE FOR A BUSY WOMAN
column14: It's not feminine, not necessarily pretty, but an AWESOME, INDESTRUCTIBLE bag. You can STUFF it to the gills. Even the most disorganized person can find her stuff easily! I like it because it functions like a mini office. The fact that the main inside compartment is light grey and not too deep makes finding what you need a snap. I have beautiful expensive Dooney's, but they are too heavy and clunky for everyday use. This bag is so light and comfortable to carry. I'm disabled and my husband does not mind holding it for me sometimes since it looks like a camera bag. The stap does not dig into your shoulder no matter how heavy the bag is, & my bag is stuffed! You can not believe how much this bag holds. I would imagine it will last for years! Excellent quality, zippers never fail, you can move the strap length easily, and it is water resistant. I'm in my mid-50's and while I sometimes wish the bag was more fashionable, for what I have to carry, this bag is just unbeatable. It's "OLD RELIABLE" for sure! Like the old Timex ads: takes a licking and keeps on ticking! Quality product.Based on this bag, I would order anything from this mfg.I can't think of any way to improve it but to say I wish it were just a bit more stylish!

column6: PUMA Unisex Liga Suede Fashion Sneaker
column14:
These shoes are beautiful... For one month or so. When I buy shoes, I expect them to be cool, to be durable, and to look good for at least a year, especially if they are made by a big brand like PUMA. These shoes are cool, they are durable, but they stop looking good after a month or so; water is their worst enemy, and do not wear them during a rainy day, for they take for ever to dry.

The material will loose its color, and will slowly start to look weird, like if it was slowly falling or being ripped apart.

Buy it only if you are okay with shoes that will last for a month or so.

column6: DC Men's Tonik Skate Shoe
column13: Comfortable, but fall apart very quickly
column14:
These shoes are comfortable and fit well, but they are not at all durable! I have been wearing them for only 5 months and they are already falling apart. Granted I walk a lot, but skate shoes are supposed to be built to stand up to hard and heavy use (you know, like skateboarding...) and these absolutely do not. The upper has separated from the sole in several places, the plastic lining is broken and poking through, there is a hole worn through the sole, and the heelcups are completely worn away with broken bare plastic showing. Remember, all this is after less than 6 months.

For what I paid ($13) I couldn't care less because for $13 I'll happily just buy a new pair every 5 months, but if you are paying more than that I do not think these shoes are a good deal.

column13: That is to say that I am always on the hunt and look out for the perfect glasses. I have purchase sunglasses to numerous to ...
column14:
I am a sunglasses nut. That is to say that I am always on the hunt and look out for the perfect glasses. I have purchase sunglasses to numerous to count in all styles and shapes ranging from 1.00 to 800.00 dollars. In all these years though I have never thought of purchasing a pair online, do to the fact that I so enjoy trying them on first, to see about there fit,style,shaping, and construction, but moreover to see how they make me feel when i put them on and look in the mirror.
When I saw these though I decided to take the plunge and i'm glad I did. These Sunglasses arrived very fast and were packaged exceptionally well in a beautiful Burberry box and hard eyeglass case. The semi cats eye shape lenses along with the Burberry designed logo side arms are incredibly beautiful and are made of high quality material,normally found on much higher priced designer glasses. As for style and fit and the way that I feel upon wearing them I can only say that these are now my absolute favorite out of the hundreds that I have.

column14: Love the color.  Love the style.  Love the patent "leather."  This is a REALLY steep heel.  My foot was nearly vertical; I felt like I was walking on my toes.
