column6: Dolce Vita Women's Nalia Wood Heel Sandal
column14: Originally I posted a rave review (see below). But I have to revise. They are beautiful and wearable but the sole is soft and very easily stained and scuffed. And a chunk of the wood by the toe just fell out. I wouldn't recommend them.  These are just beautiful. They make your ankles look tiny. Like all clogs with an ankle strap, I find I can't walk long distances but they're very comfortable for a few blocks and to stand in. The light platforms do scuff easily so you have to watch where you walk. But overall, great shoes.

column6: Skechers Mens GOBionic 2 Running Shoe
column13: Horrible pulltab/collar cushion quality which makes it frustrating to wear.
column14:
I give this product a two star solely because the cushion inside the pulltab/collar is made so purely that everytime I slip my foot inside the cushion moves down which creates a bump. After the second or third wear I was always uncomfortable walking around as I always felt like there is something nudging the top of my heel. I love Sketchers but I am very very disappointed with this product.

I only bought Go Bionic 2 because I have been wearing Go Bionic 1 for over 2 years non stop and loved how amazingly comfortable they felt on a daily use for work and exercise. They really got it wrong with this model and its heavily flawed. Please let Go Bionic 3 be flawless like the first one. I will wait for Go Bionic 3 and buy that for sure as Sketchers has only failed me once after purchased so many models.

Note: If you look closely in the photos you will see how the pulltab/collar cushion inside the shoe has been pushed forward which made stop wearing them for good

Great for wide feet. These are super comfortable, right out of the box. I was a little leary, due to the lack of reviews, but took a chance based on the low price.

Word of caution. I have wide feet. I normally wear a 9 1/2 4E, sometimes even a 10 4E. I ordered these in a size 9 M, based on a review that said that a size 9 fit large and a little wide. These are absolutely perfect for my feet. If anything they tend a little big, and fit about the same as my ASICS 10 4E. Long story short, I'd order these a size smaller than you usually wear if I were you. If you have very narrow feet you might do better to look elsewhere.

Having said that, these are still ridiculously comfy. I would absolutely order again.

Two possible detractors:

The outsole is a little slick. Not a problem outside, on trails or sidewalks. They tend to slide a little on smooth floors, like tile or hardwood. This seems to be getting better the more I wear them. Maybe I'm roughing up the soles a little.

Not very arch supportive. I've seen way worse, and they do seem to be fitting themselves to my feet the more I wear them, so maybe they'll get more supportive the longer I own them,

Did I mention that they are ridiculously comfortable? These shoes came reccomended to me by ... I went through 2 pairs of these shoes and both failed for different reasons.

I weight in at 315 pounds, am on my feet 11+ hours a day at work, I walk between 8 and 11 miles a shift in a warehouse and I have terrible arches. These shoes came reccomended to me by co-worker who has since stopped wearing them as well.

Pair 1 literally fell apart at the seams within the first few days of me wearing them. They fit fine but the stitching was so close to the edge of the material that it began to seperate. Also, the body of the shoe began coming apart from the soles. best part was that Amazon is a great place to purchase from. The new shoes were here in a couple of days. GREAT JOB Amazon ... I really can count on you!

Pair 2 lasted longer, but gradually and I am speaking weeks 3 going forward, I noticed the cushoning going away and my foot, leg and knee pain returning. By week 8 I had completely flattened the memory foam insoles to the point that they only remembered to lie there as flat as a sheet of paper offering absolutely NO support whatsoever.

I tried to insert my go-to insoles from Spenco [[ASIN:B000G1IL7C Spenco Polysorb Heavy Duty, Men's 12-13]] and because the insole is not removable in these shoes, the inserts began curling and creating a new level of foot pain for me.

I just ordered a new pair of my favorite work shoes [[ASIN:B007JTX95I New Balance Men's MX623 Cross-Training Shoe,Black,13 4E US]] that seem to do well, so much so I put the insoles into a pair I wore for almost a year every day and they kept me virtually pain free all shift yesterday. Too bad I wore out the soles before the rest of the shoe or I would not have had to order a new pair a few minutes ago.

If you plan to wear the Skechers Vigor 2.0 memory Foam shoes as a casual pair and not have to depend on them or you are one of those who love throwing away money (you can throw it at me anytime, I like to hold on to it as best I can), then these are ok shoes. If you are on your feet and think these shoes will help you make it through another shift, spend your money elsewhere.I can), then these are ok shoes. column6: Dr. Martens Vintage 1460 Boot
column13: Originals are well worth the (considerable) extra price.
column14:
These vintage series Docs are exactly what I was looking for. I have wide, high volume feet, so I will be in for a rather lengthy break in period - keep that in mind if you're buying the vintage rather than the Asian made boots. The leather is thicker, stiffer, and there is less room in the toe area due to the cap lining. The only minor quibble I have is that the eyelets are no longer stamped with "Dr. Martens" on each one like my old pair.

I read several reviews on the Asian made boots and many stated a quick or no break in period. That raised red flags for me as proper Docs take some time in my experience to mold to one's feet. Leads me to believe that the leather is of a lesser quality and that they would not have the durability I expect in a pair of boots at this price. I have an old pair that I bought in the mid 90's that look a lot worse for wear as I wore them virtually every day for a decade, but structurally they are still rock solid. Spend the extra money on the vintage series and don't look back - you won't regret it!

column6: ASICS Men's Gel Kayano 21 Running Shoe
column14: I have a couple hundred miles on this pair at most now.  The inside of the heel of one of the shoes has worn through and today I got a large blister about three miles from home and had a totally bloody sock by the time I got home.  I've been wearing Gel Kayanos since about version 11` or 13 and they always fit the same, very comfortable but with good support.  So I guess they decided to change a good thing  and stuff them with padding so only the most narrow foot will fit comfortably.  I suppose there is a wider version but good luck trying to find anything but a regular fit at a local store and I'm not risk $150 over the internet hoping they'll fit.  Final gripe: the laces are about 4-6 inches too short now for back lacing.  It is hard getting them on and off without totally undoing the back lacing.  Big disappointment.  Follow up: The heel padding broke out of the right shoe.  If I don't wear a  band aid for my 5-6 mile run I come home with the back half of my non cotton sock soaked in blood.

column13: Nice sneakers but they run small, order one or two sizes up
column14: The sneaker is nice and seems to be well made. It does run very small so I would suggest ordering two sizes up. With other brands my son is a size 7.5 or 8. Thank goodness for the free returns. At first I ordered size 8 (in red) and while it would fit my son, it didn't leave much room for growth. The insoles have a guide for the child's foot showing the correct sizing, this is a very helpful feature.  With the size 8 his toes were EXACTLY where the drawn "toes" on the insoles were which would mean they are a perfect fit. But since I want a longer use out of them I ordered the size 9 in green (because the price was better than the red in size 9).  With the size 9 his toes land EXACTLY at the insoles line that says "too big" but I felt it was still fine. He has worn the size 9 for a few days now and he hasn't tripped or had any issues. His foot is very secure and he hasn't complained of any discomfort.  I hope they are durable and hold up until he grows out of them. My son's feet aren't wide but it seems to me that a wide foot would be an issue since they seem narrow.

column13: This company needs to replace the zippers on their products...
column14:
Love the wallet. The style and size was definitely suitable for what I had been searching for. There's so many card slots inside this wallet and I like the extra flap in the middle for any extra cards I have, like my membership cards and others. There's also a pocket inside the wallet deep enough to fit my passport.
Well, I just did a review on one of the Yahoho Womens Leather Bags I purchased with this wallet and I have one basic concern, the zippers.
The zipper quality or the way it is sewn into place is absolutely terrible. The smallest amount of change placed inside the change compartment makes the zipper stick mid-way while zipping it open or close. The best was to zip the change compartment closed or open is to unsnap the wallet first then zip the change compartment. (My life is too involved and too busy to have to follow steps zipping a wallet).
This just makes me feel as though the company did not test the product for it purpose .... by not placing items inside the change compartment to make sure the zipper would work properly.

column6: Men's Bates 8 inch USMC R.A.T. Boots Olive Mojave
column14:
I received these boots 9 days ago and they are already falling apart.

Written on the inside of the tongue is the word "blemish" on both boots. The seller is clearly selling a knowingly defective product without stating so in the product listing. That's shady at best, and it should not be legal...

The sole is separating from the boot, badly on one of them. It started a few days into wearing them and is rapidly getting worse. I could probably grab it it pull it clean off easily. I will be returning these asap. It's a shame too because everything else about these boots are absoluelty perfect. I have two pair of Air Force issued boots (one regular, one cold-weather) that I have been using for years. They are great boots but starting to show their age. The Marine RAT boots are better in every possible way. They are confortable, look great and I would enjoy these for years to come if they didn't start falling apart in less than a week.

Take caution when buying these! I would not recommend buying RAT boots online unless they are made by Danner, and certainly not from Plus More Inc.

column6: adidas Performance Women's Adissage W Athletic Sandal
column14: These were my first ever Adidas purchase of this type (velcro sandal) and I fell in love. They are very stimulating to the feet so I would take caution to not over wear them at firs. Length is true to size. The colors rock. One bonus feature -- non-slip grip unlike standard "flip flops" -- ie... walk into a slippery bathroom in flip flops, you best be wearing a helmet (in my household) -- surprisingly, these are an amazingly safe sole for slippery floors even when mopping or if showering in a slippery tub it would be great for anyone with challenges in balancing or fear of falling.

column13: Not my style and not my fit.
column14: I purchased these Crocs based on the reviews I read here on Amazon as well as another website that stated these were one of the top shoes on their list. The look of them is certainly not a selling point but I was willing to forgo fashion if they were comfortable. I was purchasing these in hopes that they would provide comfort at work where I stand for 8+ hours a day. They claim to be a great shoe for those on their feet all day. Now there is a definite difference between being on your feet walking all day verses standing in the same spot. I did not feel that they were any more comfortable then a normal pair of tennis shoes. The fit through the toe box is loose, almost like wearing flip flops. The loose fit caused me issues with my toes rolling over so that I was walking on the sides of them which made for an uncomfortable fit. They are a very warm shoe due to the material they are made from and the lack of ventilation. They are now being relegated to the "quick slip on to get the mail" shoes.

column6: New Balance Men's MW812 Walking Sneaker
column13: The major trade off for me is that the foot bed of the MW812 is much more comfortable and gives more support than the MW577 does
column14: The only reason that this shoe doesn't rank a 5 star from me is an issue that I have with the construction details that affect wear ability. The issue with the MW812 is that the maker chose to minimize the top line of the shoe so that it doesn't cover the tongue properly. This is an issue with almost all modern shoes and boots. If you look for old pictures from the early 1900's until about the 1990's notice how close together the sides are. They almost cover the entire tongue. This feature allowed the foot to be cradled in the shoe aiding in lateral support as well as torsional rigidity. The modern method has the left and right side of the shoe trying to work in conjunction with the tongue to accomplish the same thing. It doesn't work as well which results in stressed feet. This lowering of the side is more pronounced on the MW812 than it is on the MW577. I find that the MW577 folds over the top of the foot to a greater degree than the MW812. The major trade off for me is that the foot bed of the MW812 is much more comfortable and gives more support than the MW577 does. Therefore I have bought 2 pairs of the discontinued MW812 shoes based on the foot bed alone and the fact that they are so affordable now. I am getting beyond the short side issue by not wearing my orthotics in them like I can do in my MW577's and I am stretching the straps by readjusting the straps periodically throughout the day.

column14:
I'm a huge fan of aviator shades, and this is my fourth pair. These shades good quality and the shade color I purchased "Flash Maui Sunset", is everything I expected and more. They're very cool looking, definitely my new favorite pair of aviators.

The outer part is very reflective and is a combination of three colors depending on the angle you're looking at. Looking through them, they really do tint your vision very dark, a pleasant dark color that is slightly orange/yellow, and they're good sun protection (UV 400 Protection) so these are perfect for wearing to the beach. They fit me well, not too loose and not too tight. So overall, I have no complaints. I do recommend carrying a glasses cleaner with you because finger print smudges really do show up on these, and I have a bad habit of accidentally touching the lenses.

So overall, I'm very happy with them, they look great.

I received this product in exchange for an honest unbiased review.

column6: Merrell Men's Moab Ventilator Hiking Shoe
column14:
I love these shoes! I had to order the Wide width for my size, and they fit exactly as I expected them to. I did try them on a few days before purchasing them on Amazon at a shoe store, which helps.

understand, I have a very wide, flat foot..... I've joked for years that I was born with snowshoes instead of feet.
So, you can imagine, it's hard for me to find shoes that I like and also fit me well.... more often than not I can have one or the other.

I get both with these shoes! And it's awesome.

I've had them for almost a year now, and I wear them, nearly, every day.

One word of caution though.... I suppose it's simply the nature of the tread pattern and the rubber used to make them, but these shoes DO NOT do well on damp surfaces like smooth asphalt, stone, or concrete...... If it's damp, wet, or raining and you have to get across a parking lot, don't run. walk slowly and just accept that you're gonna get wet.

That one caveat will not prevent me from buying another pair when the pair I have finally give up the ghost.

column6: Chaco Men's Z/2 Unaweep Sandal
column14: I rarely write reviews, but I felt compelled to write this.  Im an outdoorsman, and am on my feet a lot.  I go through a pair of sandals every summer and finally decided to get a "buy it for life" pair.  After much research on reddit, I decided to go with these. Immediately out of the box I was blown away with the ruggedness of the construction.  They're essentially a vibram sole with a fully adjustable webbing that wraps around your feet.  I knew I couldn't just put these on and start doing my outdoor activities, so I wore them casually for a week or so before wearing them hiking.  After breaking in they basically became the footwear I wear everywhere except the office.  Since purchasing, I've climbed 4 mountains with them with no problems and even started trail running with them.  The toe loop is nice and makes them grip your feet better, but when just camping and chilling next to the fire, I fold the toe loop down so I can wear socks when its cold.  My girlfriend even fell in love with them and got herself a pair.  I will likely wear them through a New England winter and probably wear them to my wedding.  I will be buying them for everyone for Christmas as they are the greatest piece of footwear I own.

column6: Ahnu Women's Montara Boot Hiking Boot
column14: Just before embarking on a 10-day hiking trip, I hurt my ankle. I knew I needed a quality boot to get me through the trip, but that ordering something sight unseen was a gamble.  I did some research and purchased the Ahnu Montara because reviewers said it was light weight, supportive and had no break-in time.  These boots are magic!!! From the second I put them on my feet, I was in love. My trip would have been ruined without them! They are comfortable, supportive but not too stiff, lightweight, and they fit like a glove. I did an 11-mile hike in these without ever having worn them before and didn't get a single blister!  I have hiked many miles in them since and they are wearing well. I am an Ahnu customer for life.

column6: Ariat Women's Meadow Western Boot
column14: This is my first pair of ankle boots ever. I'm normally a cowboy boot or tennis shoe girl, but the sale price on my size was amazing, so I thought I'd try something a little more fashionable, and I'm so glad I did. They're beautiful boots. The color is very interesting - it's not a true black as it appeared on screen. It's actually an extremely dark brown, and I find it pretty striking and different. Some of the black threading on the shaft has a slight golden shine to it in the lights, which was unexpected and a nice touch. I own several pairs of Ariat's cowboy boots, and these are true to Ariat sizing, which means you may want to order a half size smaller than your street shoe size (I'm a 6 in street shoes but a 5.5 in almost all Ariat boots I've tried on). These are snug at first, as a cowboy boot is, but they are not too tight. My heels do lift out of them slightly when I walk, but not quite as much as they do in most new cowboy boots, and this will wear off as they break in. I have no doubt they will break in very well. The quality is great as with all Ariats, and the Pendleton touch is gorgeous. They're comfortable despite the higher heel than I'm used to, as is expected with ATS footbeds. As others have mentioned, the outsole is very slick, but the heel is rubber so that helps some. Just be a little cautious on really smooth surfaces for a while. Love the fit, love the comfort, love the look, LOVE the price on Amazon for my size. I highly recommend them.

The lenses are slightly thinner than true Oakleys but fit just fine in the frames. However, I got a little bit of a headache wearing them. I didn't visually notice any distortion, but they must be off just a little bit because after 10 minutes I had to take them off.

The normal non-transition Walleva lenses are probably worth a shot for $10, but don't bother with these specifically.

column6: New Balance Grey 635 High-Performance Running Shoes - Women
column14: Loved these shoes! I'm a NB fan (8+ years) and happened across these in-store. I've put about 200 running miles on them (mostly surfaced road, some trail) and they are heading for retirement this week (replacing with NB). They did wear down a little quicker than I expected. I normally do 5-10 mile runs, so having lasted 200 miles was a bit low compared to other NB shoes I've had. They are a slightly lighter design than I normally buy so I think that had a lot to do with it. I don't have wide feet, but I'm on the larger end of average and the mid through toe box fit perfect for my size (9.5/B). The heal sat a mm or so too large but a simple heal lock fixed that personal problem.Construction wise - great quality! They actually still look pretty close to new in color and fabric! I'll continue to use them as a day-to-day shoe but are too broke down in the heal and sides to support a comfortable run.

column13: Great hands-free bag, especially for anyone using a walker or cane
column14:
Juggling a purse while using a walker is difficult and most crossbody bags I've tried are either too small to hold what I need or the strap is too short (I'm 5'7', plus-size). I need a bag that is comfortable to wear, lightweight, and has room for a large wallet, reading glasses, small adresssbook/organizer, etc. This one is PERFECT!! Very roomy (and believe me, I like roomy) and well-organized with zippered compartments that let me put things where I can easily find them. The strap is adjustable and even longer than I need and I can keep the bag on while buckled up in the car.

I HIGHLY recommend this bag and suggest you consider it for yourself and others, especially those using walker, cane, etc.

column6: Chaco Men's Outcross Evo 3 Hiking Shoe
column13: Chaco quality in a light hiking shoe
column14:
The Chaco Outcross Evo 3 is a great light hiking shoe that is "water friendly." I bought them with the intention of using them for river shoes while kayaking and canoeing. While they worked okay for this purpose, they had a tendency to hold water and let small rocks in around the ankles.

I bought my Dad a pair of Outcross Evo 2's for father's day and quickly realized that they are far better suited for river use. They are slightly lighter, drain water well, and have a neoprene liner that prevents rocks from entering around the ankle.

In hindsight I wish I would have gotten the Outcross Evo 2's for my intended use, but the Outcross Evo 3's are great for light hiking and creeking. Definitely worth keeping!

column6: Soong Classic Faux Sheepskin Faux Fur Shearling Boot
column14:
These boots are great for the price! Living in Oregon, I already know I'll need to scotch guard them to wear them outside in the wet weather.
They are cute and warm, the faux fur inside isn't too plush so your foot doesn't get all sweaty or slip inside the boot when you walk in it.
If you intend to wear or walk in these all day, I'd suggest getting arch supports and if the shallow tread is an issue go scuff the bottoms on a curb or other abrasive surface to get 'em to your liking. I'd recommend these to anyone looking for a simple, stylish boot to go with skinny jeans for winter.
The height of the shaft is good, the calf opening isn't too wide and the color is as pictured. I wear a size 9.5 US and I got a size 10 with these to ensure I can fit thick socks in them if I need to and even though I went up half a size, I'm not catching curbs when I walk :)
Love these boots AUSGERFREAKIN' can't wait for fall /winter so I can wear these!!! Hope this was a helpful review :)

column6: Pearl Izumi Men's EM Road H3 Running Shoe
column13: good support, good cushioning, cheap price - a rare combination for running shoes
column14:
Pearl Izumi makes a lot of different shoes. The H3 model name means this shoe has stability support (arch and pronation) and maximum cushioning. Other Pearl Izumi shoes have less cushioning and less support, which may be more appropriate for some people. My feet need the extra support and I've been having a hard time finding shoes with both support and cushioning. These shoes have both to keep my feet happy on long runs. The sole is pretty soft, so durability is questionable.

Sizing is a little larger than the New Balance shoes that I've been using (size 9), but not enough bigger for me to switch to a smaller size.

column13: Also has 3 slip pockets, not mentioned in description
column14: I couldn't tell from the description or photos if it had any slip pockets, and that almost caused me to go with a different wallet, but I was delighted to find it has one under each of the 3 columns of card slots. I thought maybe it would be better to have a wallet with a clear-cover for my driver's license ID, but then I thought, maybe this is more secure, in case the ID has something RF readable, and in reality, I don't have to show my ID very often anyway, so it's no big problem to pull it out. The leather is nice, and I'm glad I picked this one. True, it's larger than some other tri-folds, but not a problem with any of my pockets. I have been using rubber-bands to mold it in around the edges, as other reviewers mentioned. Very good to have so many slots to keep cards organized. I used to keep many more cards in each slot in a wallet that did not have as many slots, but note you can put more than 1 card in each slot in this one as well. They are very tight, but I'm sure they will loosen up over time.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Xbox 360 Talkback Cable with Foam Windscreen- Xbox 360
column13: Turtle Beach Quality Control Non-existent For Talkback Cables
column14: I got my Turtle Beach, X42 Headset for Christmas, 2014. It is Aug.,2015 and my cable just died. I could hear no one talking during the game. The sound of the game was coming through with no problem, it was just that I could not communicate, or hear anyone communicating. I think that it is actually not the cable, but the controller part for listening/talking to people. I just ordered THREE of these puppies, for pickup at my local Walmart, for $9.95 each. They are the Turtle Beach cables, not a knock-off/generic. I don't want to take any chances for the future, as Turtle Beach is currently out-of-stock on the cables.  There are way too many people that have had their cable die on them.  I have to believe that this is a bad design, which Turtle Beach should have corrected, long ago.  They have a good headset and strap this cheapo/defective cable to it--why?  It would seem that Turtle Beach is not interested in product quality, only product sales.  For all of the people that have given a lot of stars to this product, I have to wonder if they are reacting to the replacement solely from its' arrival and first use.  What happens after that?  Many have stated that it starts off o.k., and then essentially stops working, just like the original cable.  This essentially means that you have to keep a stock pile of cables handy, as you KNOW that the cable is going to fail at some point.  Turtle Beach is making money off the cables, by having a defective product, which people have to get, if they want to continue using their headsets.  I currently would tell folks to look for a better quality headset, and not purchase the Turtle Beach ones, unless you don't mind continually replacing the cable.  Depending on how often you had to replace the cable, this cost could add up.

column6: VRKiX Virtual Reality 3D Glasses, VR Headset for 360 Degree Viewing in Smartphone, Compatible with Google Cardboard app
column13: Nice goggles - great price - well made.
column14: I have been searching for the best VR goggles and have tried several.  Each one has its advantages and disadvantages.  This one is made well and a great deal for the price.  It has the ability to focus similar to a pair of binoculars so it works for most people and with most VR apps.  The head strap is wonderful.  The padding around the face and nose is fantastic for wearing them a long time. On the negative side I have found that Google Cardboard and DoDo Cardboard cases give the viewer a more immersive viewing experience.  The plastic headsets that I have tried seem to cause the image you are looking at to be surrounded by a border making the experience more like watching a movie and less like being immersed in virtual reality.  I have a Galaxy Note 3 so it isn't a small screen size causing the issue.  I do like these goggles. They are made well and the phone is secure inside so no one would fumble and drop the phone.  I just wish there was a way to remove the border around the screen when looking through them.

column6: PS3 Master Deluxe Non-Slip Dance Pad
column13: Good for beginners, temporary for skilled players.
column14:
I bought two pads for temporary use until I save enough money for a decent metal pad. These pads take some getting used to along with the sensitivity of the arrows. It doesn't take much to activate. I am a very skilled DDR player that has passed Max 300 on heavy with a AA and play doubles on heavy. Not saying that justifies my skill, but showing you the speed of songs at which I was used to. This pad moves A LOT for anyone who is a skilled player. Playing Exotic Ethnic on Heavy, started in front of the TV, ended up facing to the right about 45degrees and to the left about 1 foot; but I am playing on a decently thick carpet, so that is the main reason why it moves A LOT. Other than that, this will last a decent bit until I get a metal pad. Maybe 3-6 months of heavy use, I will be playing everyday after wor to get my endurance back. I have over 300+ Konami official songs, including Supernova 1 and 2; I have all the songs from "In The Groove" 1 and 2.

Another thing that I hope the seller can contact me on (I'll message him) but one of the pads has a very sticky and randomly activated down arrow. I use MotionJoy to map the pad as a XBox 360 controller so I can do jump arrows and what not so I know it isn't a mapping issue. I noticed when I stop playing during a song that when I stand on the left arrow, the down arrow gets triggered too. It consistently triggers without even touching the down arrow, I'm sure it is the pad malfunctioning.

It's a cheap pad just to get started and it will last roughly under a year, or more if you are a starter at the game.

Again if you're looking for a legit source for the network adapter then I would recommend "itembazaar" excellently priced and great packaging.

column6: Story of Seasons - Nintendo 3DS
column13: A very specific crowd will enjoy this title while the rest will not
column14:
First and foremost, it's a farming simulator. A very specific crowd will enjoy this title while the rest will not. The "grind" aspect that is repeated activity, which is often looked negatively upon in other games, is the bread and butter here. Good with that? Well all right, welcome to Story of Seasons. Reviews for this genre of game really don't have much to go on with the normal listing. Sound/music, for example, is not a strong-suit here... but it would probably have never even been something considered. Those types of categories are simple to respond to in that they're good enough to say that it's fitting.

Are you familiar with Harvest Moon? To sum up, you own a rundown or vacant plot of land to do with what you want. In the case of Story of Seasons, the goal that the game has for you is to make the town popular by managing to trade (i.e. sell your goods) with other towns that interact with yours in the form of a trade depot. More trading means more notoriety, which then means more people will want to visit and trade with the town. While this is a consistent objective, the truth is that you're simply let loose to have your own goals. Want to get to know the townsfolk better? Give them gifts and interact with them to build relationships. Want to form a romantic relationship (or relationships if that's your thing, despite consequence), get married, have a family? Just like in Harvest Moon, go right ahead. Likewise if all you want to do is make a robust farm.

The gameplay is very repetitive, but that's exactly what you should expect from this genre. It's about keeping your crops alive and maintaining an income to afford new seeds, structures, furnishing, livestock, blueprints, recipes, etc. Most crops and goods have quality ratings to them that increase the sale value the higher the rating goes. You accomplish this by fertilizing crops or by other means.

When you first start the game, there will be two difficulty choices. They REALLY make a difference for your experience early into the game, but those differences start to become smaller as time goes on (in that, eventually, the normal mode isn't as difficult to work with as the easy mode). You'll find that there really isn't a whole lot to do when you are let loose after the tutorial period. Not a lot of money and, if you're playing normal, your stamina drains so very fast when taking actions or cleaning up your land. Eventually though, this will start to change as you manage to sell more and more. As seasons change, so too will your crop selection, as certain goods can only be grown during specific times of the year.

A big part of the charm are those interactions with the townsfolk. There's a relationship system for all characters that will increase/decrease depending on your actions (notably choices during cutscenes or daily gifts you give). After you reach a certain point, you'll be able to view a cutscene about this character and learn more about them. Depending on whether or not you are a male or female character, eligible bachelors and bachelorettes are present in the game for you to woo (or crash and burn if you're bad at the game of love).

Story of Seasons is really a game that you pick up and relax to. It's not groundbreaking in any way, but it's also not bad because of that. It's simple and straightforward in how you play, but complex enough in certain areas that you might feel invested enough to do better than before. By the end of the first year in the game, there's so much to do in a given game day, that you'll laugh at how drastic of a shift it can be (depending on how you decide to build up the farm). I play it almost daily for ~1hr, and haven't really gotten bored of it since I bought it when it came out. Again though, it's definitely not a game for everyone, but it's not a bad entry to how farming sims work... as long as you pick the easy mode if you're completely new to the genre and afraid to make mistakes.

column6: Star Ocean: The Last Hope International - Playstation 3
column13: Not Worth my Time or My Money
column14:
Spoiler Alert

I'm about 20 hours into the game and I am already writing my review. That's how bad this game is. But I will try to be fair and list what I liked and not just what I didn't like:

Pro:
- The battle system was interesting.
- I liked that I could control the XP/Money/Health bonus
- Star Ocean's crafting is always fun

Con:
- Terrible voice acting. - If this came came out in 2000 then you can make allowances but dammit, I expect better acting than this. Metal Gear Solid 1 was on the PS1 and it's acting was excellent!
- Awful characters - Imagine every lame ass anime trope and cliche crammed into one game. Yup, those are your characters: the brash and inexperienced hero, the shy childhoodfriend/romance object, cat girl, obligatory child prodigy, big robot guy... Lame.
- Having only 3 basic attacks got pretty boring. You can button mash your way through every fight in the game, except bosses.
- EVERY CUT SCENE MAKES ME WANT TO SLIT MY OWN THROAT - Over the top acting, high pitch annoying voices, completely stilted dialogue.
- Ham-handed exposition

My advice to Square: Gamers playing Star Ocean aren't 10 years old anymore. You cant just cobble together a crappy script, last gen graphics, poor actors, and cliche after cliche and expect us to swallow it.

Made by Madcatz, just under a different name. Quality SUCKS. Charging base developed a contact problem after only 2 months of service and had to be replaced. Six months later, the mic wires developed a short because the flexible wire protector that swivels with it is a pisspoor design, and isn't engineered with enough slack to keep from stressing out the wires internally--which causes wire severing. After several "tickets" submitted for this issue with the Madcats.com website (that's the only way they'll deal with warranty problems), I was told that they quit making these, and they have no more replacement for them. All they would do for me was replace them with another model, that wasn't wireless, and sold for HALF as much. No thanks. I asked for a refund. They refused. I'm still trying to resolve this issue, but they told me that since I bought it on Amazon, that
I will have to take it up with them. Sorry people, but Amazon isn't the one who is supposed to take care of the warranties for the customers who shell out over $150 for each pair of these for 2 years. TERRIBLE customer service and support. TERRIBLE quality. Obsolete item and not fixable anymore. DONT BUY THESE!

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Stealth 500P Premium Fully Wireless Gaming Headset - DTS Headphone:X 7.1 Surround Sound - PS4
column13: I do like the fine tuning it gives you with chat and ...
column14:
Update: its head band have broken on both sides above the ear cuffs. Definitely wants tested well with lifespan after 8 months. I've tried to use epoxy to connect them back but they keep breaking. The plastic that they used was not meant to be bent that much. I would not buy this or anything made of the same quality of plastic. Look for something that has a metal rim to bend.

I'm basing this off of playing Destiny and watching movies with the Playstation Gold Headset for over a year.
7/10 sound
8/10 mic
7/10 comfort
4/10 usability/practicality
8/10 setup
-/10 lifespan

Sound - I work in video production so I've got an ear for sound quality. This thing, even with the bass boos preset does not have the fidelity of the PS Gold Headset. I switched between the Surround Sound and Stereo settings (because if find most 7.1 SS headsets to be hallow) and no noticeable increase in quality. I do like the fine tuning it gives you with chat and game volume.
Mic - the mic is pretty nice, easy to move around and good quality. I notice some people don't like the monitoring but i do. It picks up more specifically on peaking and when your breathing into the mic. the stuff thats annoying to hear from other people. you won't hear your own voice much though, which i find to be fine.
Comfort - its a little tight. i ware glasses and have yet to be in pain from it but its a noticeable difference and does make me fee like there is a bit of pressure on my head. But after 8 hours of use it didn't become unbearable, just noticeable.
Usability - The presets might as well just not exist. it would be more helpful to get complete control of the EQ to make them usable. like i said about the sound, very little differences in settings. I'm not a fan of the blinking LED logo that is on while the headset is powered on. I thought it was pairing at first then read it was the normal sign that it was on (considering putting tape over the LEDlogos) the adjustments for headsize are too tight to adjust while its on your head. you need to take it off to adjust. There is no way to gauge battery life outside of its audio queues of "fully charged" and "battery life low". The PS Gold headset would show battery life on screen if you hit the dashboard, same as how it shows your controller's life.
Setup - the only reason i'm giving it a 8/10 is that i have to unplug the USB dongle to switch from headset audio to TV audio. outside of that the setup is pretty quick and easy.
Lifespan - i've only had it for a month so i've not noticed a decrease or major issue with charge time or battery life. Advertised life on the box says 15 hours. i get closer to 8 when playing and chatting. still thats pretty long.

Verditc - Dont get the Surround Sound version. hardly noticeable VS stereo mode. Get the PS Gold Headsets. They are almost the same price and just work better. Only reason i got these was that the bands that compress the PS headset's earcups broke on my old pair (i may have been a little too rough with them, but i've had them since PS4 came out, so thats a good lifespan)

column6: Assassin's Creed Unity
column13: Another well-rounded addition to the AC Franchise!
column14:
I‚Äôm male gamer in late twenties, have been playing video games for the past 15 years.

First time writing a game review, overall the concept/historical representation of the game is solid but the transition of the games play/character development and dialogue is clear lack of.

I have played most Assassins Creed games, as I consider myself an occasional gamer.

Just put in 4 hours into the game and first impressions of it are mostly positive. Despite the long scene loading times, the game looks just like previous games in the franchise. When it comes to graphics I did notice smoother pixels in the characters and buildings [great balance of light and shadow: makes everything more vivid and life looking] I do play all my games on a SAMSUNG 4K UHD TV.

When it comes to combat for most part it is fluid and the controls are straight forward, I did notice when fighting multiple enemies in a small surroundings, it can be more challenging targeting enemies one by one. Running and claiming is much exciting/faster to experience compared to past games, as it more easily to move throughout the environment bouncing off objects and pillars.

I was especially impressed of the audio sound in the game throughout different part of the levels. One example of this is: when running down the stairs you can hear swords swinging and bombs exploding, getting louder and echoing thought-out the hall ways, making the play through very believable. I did see some voice glitches when multiple character are trying to talk at once ‚Äì in my gameplay this happened very little, but I had to note this.

The game is not worth its full $60 value but defiantly a must play for $19 which is the price Amazon has it listed.

Looking forward to playing Assassin's Creed Syndicate and see how the Franchise is going to take the open-word character customizability game experience to the next level. Do not disappoint your gamers UBI Soft.

I would recommend playing this game and not getting discouraged from the negative reviews written. Will continue to play the game and will update when I beat it....>

column6: ASTRO Gaming A50
column14: This is close to the worst $250 i have ever spent. The audio quality is good and the mic works fine and for the first month or two it worked fine. It's a very comfortable headset as well so I really wanted to like it. After a while though the headset would just stop functioning every so often(none of the buttons worked). You can't even turn it off. I wish I would have checked for problems regarding this headset before I bought it because that was a common problem. The only solution I could find for the problem was to let the battery die out and then charge it. The other problem I had with it was the ear pads. I know that this is a problem for other headphones as well, but why do i need to remove a plastic ring to get the ear pads back on easily  after cleaning (I didn't take mine off cause it ruins the warranty). I thought it was common knowledge that you should clean the ear pads every now and then so why not make it easier to take them on and off.  Once again this headset works great when it works, its just that it has so many problems, it isn't worth the $250 at this time. If they updated the software for it, I'd probably bump it up to 4 stars and recommend it to, but right now i wouldn't buy it again and i wouldn't tell anyone else to buy it either.

column6: dreamGEAR  Xbox One Dual Charging Dock.  Charge up to two Xbox One Controllers Simultaneously
column14:
So I received this product on 08/08/2015 and wanted to try it for a bit before I made a review. My first impressions, this charger is excellent. I'll go ahead and review a few of this devices qualities.

1. Price - I believe the price is very fair, it comes with two rechargeable battery units along with the dock, considering a unit like this in stores cost about $30-$40, I figured this was definitely a great buy

2. Looks - This looks great ! I like to keep my entertainment center looking tip top, and this sleek design with illuminated lights compliments my set up wonderfully

3. Functionality - So upon reading some of these reviews I was a bit skeptical about this product. For instance; short charge retention, difficulty removing battery unit, dock stops working, etc. However, upon using this unit I have experienced none of those problems. The battery pack is easy to take on and off, you do exactly what you would do if you were removing the Xbox battery cover. Even my 6 year old nephew can do it, no reason why you guys can't. The battery life is great ! My controllers are fully charged in about an hour and the battery last a while. I am a huge fan of ARPG, so I literally spend hours gaming, that being said, I can game for several days before having to recharge. As far as the life of the dock goes, I can not say because I've only had it for about a week, so I have no thoughts on that.

In summary, it's a wonderful charging docks and definitely worth the price. I was completely satisfied with the shipping and the price. I would recommend you pick this up, definitely worth it !

(also the light is very bright, and doesn't turn off when there are no devices charging, it doesn't bother me, but for those who keep there consoles in their rooms, this may cause an issue)

column13: If you like to chat, don't bother.
column14:
I've never been so disappointed with a product.

Pros:

Fits nicely on head
Comfortable over ear
Nice Sound Quality

You'd think with those good features that it would get a good review, but I just can't do it. When it works, it's great, the problem is that about half the time it doesn't work and the mic doesn't receive sound at all. If you try to unplug and reset the mic, 9 times out of 10, you'll lose complete control of your xbox. This means the only way to get control of your xbox again is to completely shut it off and back on. When you only have an hour to game and you spend 50 minutes getting your mic working it sucks ... every time.

If you want to just listen, go ahead, but if you like to use your headset to chat, save yourself the trouble and under no circumstances should you ever consider buying this headset.

column6: HORI Real Arcade Pro 4 Kai for PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3, and PC
column14: The RAP 4 Kai is a competitively priced fightstick for the PS4 whose value is undermined by its inconsistent build quality. I used the stick for about three days before sending it back because the 'Share' button would occasionally activate without pressing it during gameplay. I can't say if the issue is widespread as I only tested one unit, but even if I were to judge it without taking the defect into account, my experience with the stick convinced me to get a refund instead of a replacement.  Hori has opted to use their own proprietary joystick and pushbuttons, Hayubasa and Kuro respectively, instead of the standard Sanwa parts. Fortunately, the Hori parts are of good quality. Whether you like them or not will come down entirely to personal preference. As far as the stick is concerned, I found the engage and throw distances a bit too long, but again, that's just preference. The only real difference I noticed was that the Hayabusa is a tad stiffer than the JLF, but honestly you probably won't notice or care about the minute differences between it and the Sanwa. If you like the JLF, you'll probably like the Hayabusa. The pushbuttons feel somewhere between Sanwa and Seimitsu in terms of resistance, with Sanwa being the most sensitive, the Kuro slightly less so, and Seimitsu buttons being the stiffest of the three brands. All in all, the Hayabusa joystick and Kuro buttons are perfectly competent components. But together they can be had for around $50 retail if you were to buy the joystick and buttons separately. The cost to Hori, not including the case and wiring, is a fraction (probably 1/3, around $15-$20) of that seeing as they manufacture the parts themselves. So where is the rest of your money going?  The one thing that this stick has going for it is that includes a touchpad, which the latest Madcatz sticks still lack as of this review (update: they now come with touchpads). Beyond that though, Hori went cheap with the rest of the fightstick, straight up. The moststriking example is the thin, flimsy cord compartment door. Any pressure from the cord will have it open if not entirely pop out of its hinges. Additionally, the casing itself feels like it's made of lightweight cheap plastic. As another reviewer mentioned, the RAP 4 Kai does not feel like a $150 controller. Unfortunately, I can't tell you anything about the internals because opening the stick voids the warranty.  Besides the low-quality build, Hori made some questionable design decisions with this stick. For starters, the 'Option' button is large and placed right on the face next to the functional buttons making it very easy to accidentally hit it during a match. Moreover, the porous black plastic on the majority of the stick is a  magnet for finger grease that's really difficult to clean. Additionally, the RAP 4 is not mod friendly in the least. You'll need to remove numerous screws, and subsequently screw them all back in, to get at the internals. Lastly, the switches, L3, R3, PS, Share, and Turbo buttons are placed on the right side of the stick, out of view, which means that if you need to flip a switch or press one of these buttons you'll have to turn the stick sideways to find the correct one.  When compared to the $200+ Madcatz sticks, the RAP 4 Kai seems like a good value, but this is an illusion. Both the RAP4 and Madcatz TE2 are overpriced, the TE2 especially. Currently, no manufacturer is offering a fightstick for the PS4 that is worth the premium price they're asking. The RAP4 needs to be either cheaper in price or higher in quality.  EDIT: I raised it a star  EDIT 2: Had to lower it back to 2/5 after experiencing the exact same 'Share' button issue with a friend's stick.  So TL;DR: It's a competent, if flawed, entry-level stick provided you get one that isn't defective.

column6: XCOM: Enemy Within
column14:
Finally got around to playing this, and it's not a whole lot different than the prior version... more stuff here, but essentially the same story. I probably would love this game, as it feels scary, mysterious and exciting. But there are just a couple of things that lower my rating. First, the quarter turn viewpoint is terrible because you cannot really check out if you are in the perfect spot, or an "okay" spot, in relation to the enemy. This should be like most computer games that have 360 smooth rotation and you can stop it anywhere. Secondly I seem to always have problems getting a soldier to climb a ladder and get onto a roof. When it works, it's cool, but most of the time, my solder moves to another location on ground level and if there are enemies nearby, chances are, they are fully exposed. The last gripe I have is that every time you tell a solder to get ready to fire at anything that moves, it forces you to click on an "OK" box, as there is a message that describes about what you just selected, and do you want to do that for sure. When you're first learning, that is good. But when you KNOW what you want to do, which is the case 99.99% of the rest of the time in the game, that box SHOULD NOT pop up.

On the good side, the explosions are pretty, the story is pretty good, although a little "hammy" with the heavy German accent of the Head of Research (which is very humorous. (fyi: I'm of German descent and have nothing against Germans!) And then there's the head of Manufacturing, which I tell you, looks uncannily like Dick Cheney!

It's a hard game, even on Easy.

column6: Dragon Age Inquisition
column14:
It was a MASSIVE disappointment. I've had the game for close to a year now- got it on release day, a waste- and honestly I've never been able to get past the first section of the thing. Below is a list of the points that have killed this franchise for me- and possibly turned me away from Bioware and EA entirely.

-1- My biggest problem was with the amount of crashes and bugs within the game. And this is despite the patches and updates. The audio files all but crashed the entire game, the cut scenes ran about as well as reading a comic(absolutely no fps so I skipped or forced a skip if the cut scene wouldn't allow it), there were triggers for cut scenes that never triggered(what stands out quite a bit is the actual intro, in which my character was stranded inside a desolate caldera, unable to move forward as it flagged me as "currently in a cut scene"), -and god forbid you if you try and customize your character with more than a different hair color! It actually killed- and killed as in, windows OS entirely cracking and wiping everything within my HDD- my other laptop when I was trying to make a character.
-2- The open world-ness. The ridiculous amount of fetch quests and absolutely unrewarding objectives that were scattered throughout a massive map killed the urgency that seemed prevalent to the previous games("ooh my! You have miss-placed your cattle on the other side of the map! Let me and my merry band of dolts fetch them for you!"). Honestly, whenever I sloughed through the time it took to open the map, I amused my self by thinking some project manager had simply put the map on a wall and thrown darts to pick objective locations.
-Thats it- I could go on, but that should be enough. Keep in mind, the game is lacking in everything its predecessors made great and it has almost zero playablilty. If you want a good paper weight with a Dragon Age series theme, get this game! Its great at just sitting there!!

column6: PlayStation Headsets
column14: I was pretty excited to get these.  I did a fair amount of research, and most of the reviews are excellent.  First off, my #1 criteria was sound quality.  I was looking for the best sound, without spending almost as much on a headset as I did on the PS4.  These seemed to fit the bill.  During my research, I had found people recommending buying a sound processor and a decent pair of headphones instead.  Since I already had a decent pair of stereo phones (Sony MDR-7506), I decided to also get the Turtle Beach Ear Force DSS 7.1 Surround Sound Processor (I also had the necessary optical audio cord, and mini USB power cord), and do a side-by-side test just for fun.  Holy crap was the difference night and day.  I listened to the Playstation Gold headset first, and it sounded good until I plugged the MDR-7501s into the processor.  The 7501s absolutely blew the golds away.  No contest.  Side-by-side, the Golds are flat, dull, and muffled while the MDRs were crisp, loud, and dynamic.  If you are looking for immersion, buy yourself a decent pair of headphones (not Beats by Dre), and get a standalone processor.  Sure, it's not wireless, but if your main goal is great sound quality and immersion, you can't go wrong.

column6: Batman: Arkham Knight
column14:
Batman Arkham Knight has a lot of good going for it and some things that are bad for it as well. Sadly, the good things about this game have been done before in the previous versions and the things that bring this game down, REALLY bring it down.

First the good: The graphics and and gameplay remain great and the graphics really shine on the consoles but of course it is at 30fps. I imagine that the freeflow combat would have been amazing to see even more if it was 60fps but we gotta deal with the limits of our next gen consoles, oh well. It is still satisfying to be Batman and fight like an intelligent, skillful and fearless fighter and also glide around the city.

Sadly, those are the only good things I can think of about this game but let's be honest, the same good things in Arkham Knight were also done in Arkham City. As awesome as it feels to be Batman, it also feels like the developers didn't know, forgot how to or just didn't care to give Batman competition this time around. All of Batman's infamous enemies that you come across, don't feel special at all this time around. In previous games, there were boss fights but in this game there are pretty much none.

Even when I thought there was going to be a boss battle either it became a simple takeout like any other grunt soldier, then cut scene then Batman takes them to jail or it is a boring tank battle, cut scene and Batman takes them to jail. There are no epic or memorable fights in this games, just some memorable cut scenes.The enemy who will give you the most trouble will be The Riddler because of his tedious riddles and trophies which by the way, you have to collect all of them this time around to get the complete ending. I feel that is a horrible way to acquire the most complete ending. Me and I feel most other people out there who have a lot of games to play or limited time, would rather Youtube the ending then putting in frustrating amounts of time to do something as tediousas collecting trophies throughout a huge area over 200 times just to get the most satisfying ending.

After viewing the complete ending on Youtube (because I just didn't want to be bothered with the Riddler trophies) I can say it wasn't worth the effort that the developers expect of the player to achieve it. The story itself before the ending was actually pretty good overall. Not great but entertaining to say the least. The ending combined with a strong emphasis on the Batmobile/tank battles really bring this game down. As for the replay value, it may always be fun to fight as Batman but it eventually gets old and after the complete ending there are only challenges left to do but those are even more frustrating and tedious than The Riddler trophies. I also had problems trying to play the DLC stories. Apparently it is a common problem that these can't be accessed after we redeemed and installed them. I tried restoring my licenses on my PS4 but I still wasn't allowed to play the Harley Quin and Red Hood story packs. My interest in this game died completely after I got one of the endings but that isn't to say it wasn't all bad . I just don't recommend this as a $60 buy.

column6: Titanfall
column14:
Being mediocre at the Call of Duty games can get frustrating. All the equalizers in the game are based on kill streaks, which once one falls behind they typically get left behind (pirate code). The great part of this game is no matter how bad one is doing, every three minute, give or take, you get to call down a giant robot and run around and wreak havoc.

Mixed in with a bunch of unlockables for load outs (similar to call of duty) for both your person and Titan (giant robotic killing machine) this game is a lot of fun to play. The only place it falls short is the campaign. In a typical unreal tech fashion they neglected to make a true campaign. Instead of a story you just play the computer in multiplayer games and win or lose you move on to the next. More of a single player mode than a campaign. With so much potential for an awesome story, it would have been nice if they bothered to make one.

column6: Far Cry 4
column13: Same as Far Cry 3 - Well Almost but just better!
column14:
For anyone planning to buy a good game, this is it. However, if you have played Far Cry 3, you might be disappointed by how similar the two are in game play. (even though Far Cry 3 was a superb game in itself)
Here are some of the "upgrades":
1. Buzzer: No more driving miles just to get to the next outpost or tower. Just fly around in your private little buzzing flying machine!
2. Elephants: You can break into an outpost sitting on an elephant and it's way more effective! (you have to learn the skill first though)
3. Karma points: Do good deeds and get more karma (unlocks certain things but not really anything major)
4. Arena is kind of renamed and the concept has become more close to it's name compared to the one in Far Cry 3
5. Fortresses: Much more strongly guarded outposts but pretty much the same concept.
6. Outpost Master: Play the same outpost again in case you wanted to try a different technique
7. Many more decision paths in playing the missions: Adds some replay value

Plus on top of that
-I think the Missions are slightly better.
-They have added more collectibles as well which is kind of annoying when you want a 100% game completion but helps a lot to get skill points and karma quicker.
-Slightly changed interface to syringes and auto crafting of health syringes

A very good first person shooting game nonetheless for first time buyers. Probably one of the best I have played.

column6: Project CARS
column13: TLDR: This is the most fun I've had playing a racing game.
column14:
First copy shipped from Amazon was an empty case, no disc. It wasn't shrink wrapped, no sticker, nothing. I suspect this one was a "display case" for people working in the warehouse and it got sent to me by accident, but it would be interesting to hear if this happened to anyone else. I contacted Amazon, and they shipped a replacement with free 1 day delivery, so in the end I was satisfied.

Unlike Gran Turismo and many other racing games, there's no "grinding" to unlock cars or mods, which makes the single player career mode refreshingly fun right from the start. It features a number of racing disciplines, including karts, GT cars, touring cars, road cars, LMP prototypes, and a few open wheel variants similar to Formula 1, you can start your career where ever you like, however there are special achievements for starting at the beginning and working your way up. Online multiplayer is a blast if you race with the right people, but can be frustrating when lower skilled drivers bump and ram, but that can happen in any public online racing games. Online leaderboards/time trials are extremely poorly done, and in my opinion one of the biggest drawbacks of the game. Best lap times are grouped by car class, so you can really only race one or two cars in any given class if you want to be competitive... and that also means you only get one entry per class at each track. I can't set a fast lap in my favorite road car *AND* the fastest road car, so I have to pick which I'd rather have appear on the board. Car selection is not that large compared to Gran Turismo, however there is enough variety in most classes that it doesn't matter too much, and all cars are unique in their handling so you won't feel like you have 20 different models of the same thing in your garage. Some of the most popular car manufacturers are left out, particularly Japanese and Italian companies seem to have a very small representation. Vehicles can't be modded, but canbe tuned... tweaking all sorts of settings including (just to name a few) tire pressures at each corner, brake balance and pressure, roll bar stiffness, suspension height and damping, and much more. The cars also can't be painted custom colors, but they each have a few pre-made "liveries" to allow for some visual variety in races. Physics are amazing, but extremely challenging when compared to some other racing games. The graphics are spectacular, a night race in a thunderstorm on a remote poorly lit track is particularly breathtaking, and watching the sunrise near the end of a 24 hour Le Mans run is equally remarkable. Some areas of the game are not done, and there are a few bugs that can be very frustrating. Normally I would drop my rating for it, but in this case I've seen the game's development team being extremely active with the community in finding and resolving the bugs, so I am confident that this game will quickly be improving.

To get the best experience, I would *HIGHLY* recommend playing this game with a steering wheel and pedals. It brings the immersion to a whole new level. Force feedback isn't the best by default, but it's extremely customizable, to a level I've never seen before. The large number of FFB settings can seem daunting, but the community has an excellent collection of "alternate" feedback settings that really clean it up and make it easy to feel the road and the car reacting to it. Unfortunately, entering these settings is unique per car (and even per track if you don't do it ahead of time from your garage), which can become a long and tedious process, but in the end is worth every minute spent dialing in the numbers. I recommend starting with just a few cars settings while you figure out which "set" of FFB settings you like most.

Overall, this is the most fun I've had playing a racing game, and I've played just about all of them.

column6: Skylanders Trap Team
column14:
My son is 6 and got this for Christmas. He LOVES it! He's been wanting Skylanders but we already had an iPad and he just got a DS for his birthday so I didn't want to buy another gaming system like a Wii, Xbox, etc. I was excited to see this in the tablet version. He's able to play with the figurines at home and play some of the game on the go with the codes. He likes that he can buy the older Skylanders and they work too.

Battery life on the portal is pretty good. It's about what I expected it to be. We went through 24 batteries in no time but he was playing it a lot over Christmas break and I bought the cheap batteries for low draining devices. I bought some better batteriers and they don't seem to drain as fast.

I just hope that Activision doesn't come out with a new set year and focuses on Trap Team for another year or so. It would be disappointing if they did. I noticed that the store shelves are packed with Swap Force and Giants starter packs. Not sure why you'd buy either of those now because they won't play Trap Team. They're basically outdated unless you only want to be able to play the older Skylanders. Hopefully Activision will take note of this and not outdate itself too soon.

column6: PDP Wired Fight Pad for Wii U
column13: Excellent for what you need it to do
column14:
In terms of third party products, PDP often stands tall as a maker of quality goods. This pad is no exception. The pad features very spring-y buttons, responsive analog pads, and a good sized d-pad.

On the subject of buttons however, the L and R triggers are in fact digital triggers, not analog. This is not a deal breaker by any means, but it's something to keep in mind and it was worth a star to me.

If you're considering buying one of these pads, it's probably for Super Smash Bros. If that's the case I can assure you this is a fine pad for it. I've been using it for some time, and have not had a single issue with it. Serious competitive players though will tell you that you need a gamecube wired controller for Smash Bros, and I won't disagree. There's always a feeling of confidence when you're on an official wired pad.

That being said, if you're not in a tournament with a cash prize or your freedom on the line, this is a fine Pad to use for Super Smash Bros, or for playing Virtual Console games on your Wii or Wii U. Just don't play SNES games with this pad, the gamecube button layout is not friendly to SNES games. It's great for just about every other VC games though.

column6: Nyko Charge Base
column14:
My last Xbox controller charger I bought was an Energizer for my Xbox 360 and I never had a problem with it. This one however had a few kinks that needed to be worked out. The main problem being that even though the controller will stop charging when the device believed they are fully charged is wrong. When you turn on the Xbox they are slightly consumed according to the Xbox battery reader. Now this is no big deal since I'm not usually playing games for 8 hours straight and don't need that extra two hours to continue gaming. However, I could see this being a concern to many other people.

Secondly I could installing the battery packs quite easy even though others found it difficult. The arros pointed me in the right direction and the + - was correct as well. They charge at a fast rate as well. All in all I would recommend this product to someone who doesn't want to pay a lot of money to charge their controllers, but if you have a few extra bucks I would recommend the Energizer, you will be much happier and can use rechargeable batteries instead.

column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column14:
Well today I gave The Elder Scrolls Online‚Äã a second chance. Remember Skyrim? I was level 81.5 (the maximum) and had mastered every type of play. It was always fun, always kept me engaged, and had few boring moments. ESO takes SOOOO LONG to get anything done. there is no clear tutorial or explanation about how to do simple things like crafting or learn your fighting buttons. This is NOT an Elder Scrolls game, its a Warcraft game by Bethesda Soft.

This game is dark. and I don't mean gritty or gory. I mean its pitch black in some interior spaces. Even with a 5 bar connection to the North American server the controls are lagging. Almost all of the items I picked up in the first few missions were worth ZERO at the vendors. Combat is lame. Push Buttons, swing sword. Power attack = Counter opening. Lame. All of the cool stuff costs "crowns" like any game nowadays with tons of dlc add ons. Bethesda has sold out and lets hope Fallout 4 is the comeback.

What makes me mad the most is the lack of transferable account. When I upgraded from Xbox 360 to Xbox One I received COD Ghosts season pass FOR FREE ($42 value). When I logged into ESO with my old account from the launch PC version, I GOT NOTHING. I didnt get back my Imperial edition. Is it so hard for Bethesda to transfer this information over? Its not like Xbox and Microsoft's Games for Windows are from different companies.

This is getting traded in tomorrow. Feel free to comment but nobody is changing my mind.

column6: Splatoon
column13: Not without its problems but still a good game.
column14:
The gameplay is of this game is addicting and unique, the theme and style is awesome, it has really good graphics, a really good art style, and the game has been expanding over time with new weapons, maps, modes, and tweaks to existing content. The single player is fun and challenging and the Amiibo support, while not the best, feels worth it.

The downside is there's a weapon imbalance that is especially noticeable at high level play. The game isn't super laggy but lag hurts the game badly at high level play due to no regional matchmaking. You can only group up with friends in ranked battles. Maps you play on are randomly selected from 2 maps that are changed every 4 hours. There's no voice chat. You can't see your teamates weapons until the battle starts. You can't choose new weapons during gameplay or between rounds (in turf war at least). The local multiplayer is not up to par either with only one on one battles, no campaign co-op, and no taking friends locally online.

Ultimately though, while the downsides of Splatoon are definitely worth noting and they do hurt the game, they don't hurt the game enough to make the game not fun. The gameplay and style far outshines the areas it's lacking in. It's not the perfect game, but it's a great new IP and first attempt by Nintendo on a genre that's oversaturated.

column6: Xbox One Wireless Controller [Without Bluetooth]
column13: Quality control issues mar an otherwise stellar product
column14: This controller aces so many criteria that I am loathe to give it anything less than a stellar review. The ergonomics are perfect, the shoulder buttons drastically improve upon the inordinately stiff buttons of the original, the D-pad feels tight and responsive, and it's as plug-and-play as one would expect. And yet, here I am giving it a middling review because of a lack of quality control. Within two days of light to moderate use, the right trigger on my brand new controller developed a stickiness when releasing the trigger back to its neutral position. The left trigger did not exhibit this problem but it also didn't see nearly as much use as the right (I had been playing Burnout: Paradise). I realize I may have received a bum controller -- manufacturing defects happen, after all -- but my first brush with this controller has left a sour taste in my mouth; a far cry from my storied legacy with its nigh-indestructible 360 predecessor.   After reading some other negative reviews for this product (thumbstick rubber wearing out, connectivity problems with the 3.5mm port), I'm hesitant to give the controller a second chance. Here's hoping the next revision irons out these issues.

column6: Nintendo - New 3DS XL Legend of Zelda: Majora's Mask Limited Edition - Gold/Black
column13: New Majora's Mask 3DS was definitely worth it
column14:
A bit pricey since I wasn't able to get this at launch but the system was definitely worth buying. I have the Limited Edition Legend of Zelda: A Link Between Worlds 3DS XL so when I saw ANOTHER limited edition Legend of Zelda 3DS I knew I had to have it eventually. I really like the design, more so than the A Link Between Worlds 3DS XL. It only comes with a 4GB micro SDHC card but I was prepared. Before buying this 3DS, I had already bought a 64GB micro SDXC card and configured it to FAT32 since that's the only type of SD card the 3DS supports. I then transferred everything on my current A Link Between Worlds 3DS's SD card to the new 64GB SDXC card with the help of a SD card adapter. As soon as this new majora's mask 3DS arrived, I performed the system transfer and now I have a 64GB SDXC that will easily last for the lifecycle of this 3DS.

You can instantly tell the 3D is a lot better on the new 3DS just from configuring it during the initial system setup! You can navigate through the main menu a lot smoother as well thanks to the increased processing power. I've only been playing Pokemon (ORAS) so far so I'm not sure how the little C-nub handles. I'd have to play a game that utilized it and get back on that.

Anyways, if you're a Legend of Zelda fan or just a avid collector, you should definitely get this if you weren't already one of the lucky ones to get it at launch. The price will only go up from here so I HIGHLY recommend buying this soon if you're still indecisive at this point. You won't regret it months from now when the price is even higher,

column6: Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection
column13: I bought it twice because I had both consoles in different rooms and I love these classic games enough that I want them availabl
column14:
I've owned this game for some time on both the Xbox 360 and PS3. Yes, I bought it twice because I had both consoles in different rooms and I love these classic games enough that I want them available in two different spots.

That being said, this collection is the single biggest collection of Sega games on a single compilation, and to this day it's easily the best compilation ever released by any company on any console.

There are 49 games total, if you include the second version of Altered Beast, and for the price you're paying, you'll easily get hundreds of hours of entertainment from this disc. There isn't a single game on the disc that I dislike, but your own taste may vary. Primarily, I play the Phantasy Star games on this disc, and they alone would be worth the price of the collection. But there are other gems strewn across the whole collection. Kid Khameleon, the Sonic Games, Alex Kidd, Streets of Rage, etc.

I gave the collection 5 stars because of rounding. I would have given it 98 of 100 on that scale. The 2 lost points would be for 1) Where is Toejam and Earl? and 2) We really wanted Sonic 3 + Knuckles in this set.

That disclaimer aside, if you're a fan of classic Sega Games or good games in general, get this set, you won't regret it.

column6: Dragon Age Inquisition
column14: When a developer tells you that their game is going to be an "open world" your first reaction might be "Hey, that's great! Lots to do, worth my hard earned dollar." The reality however of an open world, after playing several games of this genre, is that the open world experience is only as good as the creators of it make it. Unfortunately Bioware opted to include an over abundance of go and fetch it quests that do not advance the storyline or gain the player any significant items, weapons or armor. By the middle of the game, I was able to craft armor and weapons that were much better that the ones I acquired by pursuing a long and tedious quest through insanely inaccessible terrain. After a certain point I just gave up on collecting shards, astariums, occularium et cetera. These "quests" felt more like chores and so much filler that Bioware inserted into the game to bulk up their open world experience.   Having said that, DAI has a lot to offer players including memorable characters, an interesting (but somewhat predictable) story, nice graphics and character creation options, great combat mechanics, new and in-depth skills, and the ability to make choices throughout the game that do truly affect events in the game. It is obvious that Bioware spent a lot of time making sure that the player is truly immersed into the culture and history of Thedas and it is a feature of any game that I enjoy and respect from the developers. A game well worth your precious time and money. I just hope that if there is another installment of this game that they focus more on content intricate to the story than on meaningless quests and acquisitions.  On a side note the Xbox One version of this game plays much better than the 360 version to the point of being an almost completely different experience.
