column6: Thrustmaster VG T300RS Racing Wheel Servo Base for PS4 and PS3
column13: Would seriously consider going back to Logitech with their new g29 if I had to make the purchase again.
column14:
The first wheel I purchased broke within the first month of casual usage (roughly 20-30 hours of use). After looking around online, it seems to be pretty common for this model to fail quickly. Expecting no issues with support since this was common, I contacted Thrustmaster directly to try to get it fixed, but they were of no help whatsoever. It took them over a week to reply to my support ticket, and once they did, they refused to offer any sort of support unless I connected the wheel to a windows PC for troubleshooting (which I could not). They even continued to refuse support after I provided the company with multiple videos that clearly highlighted 3 major failures with the wheel, one of which had rendered it completely useless.

If this item is sold as a ps4 accessory Thrustmaster needs to support it as a ps4 accessory!

Luckily Amazon came to my rescue. Even tho I was past the exchange period with Amazon, I explained to their support staff that the wheel had failed within that period, and I had tried to get support directly from the manufacturer but they refused. Amazon took it back, no further questions asked, they didn't even ask to see the videos of it failing! They sent me a replacement wheel of the same model. So far it hasn't failed... and I'll keep my fingers crossed that it lasts.

The replacement wheel works great so far, the force feedback is smoother and stronger than my old Logitech G25, it's also a little quieter because it doesn't have the gear chatter that the logitech wheels have. However, the wheel has a cooling fan that turns on after a certain amount of use. This fan isn't overly loud, but it's definitely noticeable. In my opinion the fan noise is a little more annoying than the logitech gear chatter, but with the volume up an extra notch it's easy to forget. If the wheel gets too hot from continued use at high feedback settings, the feedback will cut out completely until it cools. The company says this is to protect the motors from damage, but I think it's a function of poor design. My Logitech wheel would last for 12+ hour endurance races at it's highest feedback setting without an issue, and lasted me 5+ years in that fashion.

The stock pedals are horrible, and serious racers will want to upgrade them immediately. There's no clutch pedal, and the brake has a very springy feel that doesn't feel natural, and makes it difficult to consistently apply partial pressure when braking. The Thrustmaster T3PA Pro pedals are a good replacement set to pair with this wheel, offering a much better brake feel and a clutch pedal.

Overall, it's good when it works. Hopefully it works. Inexcusable lack of support from Thrustmaster. Would seriously consider going back to Logitech with their new g29 if I had to make the purchase again.

column6: Mayflash GameCube Controller Adapter for Wii U and PC USB, 4 Port
column13: It just works like the real thing
column14:
NOTE: I do not have Smash Brothers for the WiiU so I cannot comment on its performance in that respect.

I got this to play Gamecube and Wii games with the Dolphin emulator using an authentic controller, and it works absolutely flawlessly. All you have to do is get the driver for it (which can be found on the Dolphin wiki through google), set it to WiiU mode, and then click "Direct Connect" in the controller menu. After this, it works perfectly. You don't even have to set up the buttons, calibrate the stick, or adjust deadzones. It just works like the real thing. Easily worth your time if you want to play Dolphin with an authentic controller. As a tournament player of Super Smash Brothers Melee and a fan of F-Zero GX, both games which require extremely fine and correct inputs, I can say that these work great. I can SHFFL and Wavedash in Melee just like the console, and I can control the finicky machines of F-Zero GX just like the console. Simply amazing!

column6: SteelSeries Siberia X300 Comfortable Gaming Headset for Xbox One, Xbox 360
column14:
Badass headphones with nice versatility.

First off the sound from these is better than expected.¬† Nice deep bass and acceptable high range.¬† The inclusion of multiple connectors is a welcome addition too.¬† The base phones use a 4-part miniplug like a pair of phone headphones.¬† This can be plugged into the xbox adaptor to get sound through your controller (the xbox doesn't shut off the tv sound automatically when you do this which is dumb) or straight into your smartphone to listen to music or make calls.¬† Included is also a splitter that turns them into the more common for computers seperate mic and speaker cables.

The cord is LONG.¬† For a set of phones that're sold for use with a controller it's a bit too long.¬† This makes me suspicious these were designed for someone to use elsewhere and repurposed.¬† The ear covers are big-ish and give pretty good isolation.¬† The headband adjustment is automatic and works quite well to keep hard bits off of your head.¬† My only complaint is it squeezes a little on my big (XXL helmet) noggin.

I am not a fan of the microphone mute on the phones themselves which is behind the let ear -- not a natural location.¬† If you're using the Xbox connector this is a non-issue.¬† The mic is serviceable but well hidden.

column6: Toy Soldiers: War Chest Hall of Fame Edition
column13: Great game! Best of the series
column14:
I'm a pretty big fan of this series, and strategy games in general, I got both of ones on 360 the day they came out and enjoyed them for quite some time, I still play Cold War on Xbox one, and war chest is personally my favorite of the bunch. I didn't think I would enjoy it as much from the gameplay I saw of unicorns and fairies as enemies but they do add a different feel to the game, along with the normal military themed enemies. There's a lot more content in this one, you can buy/unlock a bunch of upgrades for your heroes and defensive weapons which is a nice touch. There's 8 armies in the game(I only have 4 since I bought the digital copy for $15), all of their defenses are different which is pretty cool, each one plays pretty differently so that adds to the replay value. The campaign maps are all really cool, you go from d-day style maps to fighting in a strawberry princess type of maps, very varied. There's also online coop and verses mode, verses mode I don't like but coop is quite fun.
Will say I have experienced extreme frame drop lags when the action gets going a few times,mostly when you're playing as the hero.
But overall for the price, $30 for 8 armies, $15 for 4 it's a pretty good steal and with the amount of content it should keep you entertained for a while,

column6: PlayStation 2 Power Cord (Bulk Packaging)
column14: Product shipped is not what is being advertised. The pictures and description clearly say that this cable has a "square+round" plug matching the shape of the PS2 power socket. The cord that they are currently shipping is "infinity" shaped. I returned the first one and got back another incorrect one. They probably didn't even read my "reason for return". Technically this will work and power your PS2, but the reason I bought this was to have one of the correct shape.

column14: This is so great for those of "us" that just cannot pull off the racing games with just the controller (insert my sons laughter here). This snapped on easily and made it a better experience for me as I like to feel like I am actually steering while racing. Actually beat my son once or twice. Although I received this item at a discount for a fair and honest review I will be buying another as my son doesn't think it is a fair race anymore and would like his own.

column6: Friday the 13th
column13: IT'S MADE BY LJN! ENOUGH SAID!!!
column14:
It's made by LJN! That alone makes this game a masterpiece!!!!!!

I'm dead serious and am not trolling you at all!

Why, Jason looks absolutely pimpin' and fabulous in purple and whoever came up with the trajectory for the really effective rock and the totally not frustrating maps that work the opposite the way you want, or the mind blowing 3d cabin scenes which are so easy to use is a GENIUS!!!

By that, I mean an evil genius. This game was obviously put together by a bunch of laughin', jokin' numbnuts who only cared about money and not about quality.

All in all, 5 stars, because it's one LJN's finest works!
